  "lessons": [
    {
      "key": "lesson-1",
      "name": "Pre-Assessment",
      "absolute_position": 1,
      "lockable": true,
      "has_lesson_plan": false,
      "relative_position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "assessment": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-1",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "ai-powered-threats-and-defenses-pilot-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-4",
      "name": "Lesson 1: Introduction to Cybersecurity",
      "absolute_position": 2,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How does cybersecurity affect me in my every day life?**\n\nThis lesson introduces students to the concept that cybersecurity isn’t just about malicious attackers. Systems can also fail due to technical glitches, human error, or poor design. These failures can lead to frustration, harm, or even lost opportunities. By reading the story of a student whose school day goes very wrong, students analyze the human, technical, and data aspects of everyday breakdowns and begin to explore the foundational challenges that cybersecurity seeks to address.",
        "preparation": "- Print copies of the Unit Guide (one for each student)",
        "student_overview": "**How does cybersecurity affect me in my every day life?**\n\nLearn how cybersecurity involves more than just malicious attackers by exploring how technical glitches, human error, and poor design can cause real-world problems."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-4",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "ai-powered-threats-and-defenses-pilot-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-5",
      "name": "Lesson 2: Cybersecurity Threats",
      "absolute_position": 3,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How do AI-enhanced cyber attacks exploit system vulnerabilities?**\n\nStudents recognize how digital systems can be exploited through technical flaws or misconfigurations, and how these threats affect the integrity and availability of services. They explore one of the threats in depth to learn more about how it works.",
        "preparation": "- Print copies of the Cybersecurity Threats activity guide (one for each student)",
        "student_overview": "**How do AI-enhanced cyber attacks exploit system vulnerabilities?**\n\nLearn how cybersecurity threats attack system vulnerabilities and and misconfigurations to compromise digital systems."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-5",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "ai-powered-threats-and-defenses-pilot-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-6",
      "name": "Lesson 3: Phishing and Password Attacks",
      "absolute_position": 4,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How do cyber attacks exploit human vulnerabilities, i.e. trust, emotion, and predictable behavior?**\n\nIn this lesson, students analyze how cyber attackers exploit predictable human behaviors—such as trust, emotion, and oversharing—to gain access to accounts. They examine phishing messages, investigate fictional breach reports, and use AI to evaluate how attacks work and why they succeed. The focus remains on human vulnerability rather than technical exploits.",
        "preparation": "- Provide copies of the Hackable Human activity guide (one for each student)",
        "student_overview": "**How do cyber attacks exploit human vulnerabilities, i.e. trust, emotion, and predictable behavior?**\n\nExplore how hackers trick people by using personal details and predictable habits. Investigate real-looking messages and breach reports to figure out how attackers break in—and what you can do to stop them."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-6",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "ai-powered-threats-and-defenses-pilot-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-7",
      "name": "Lesson 4: Phishing with AI",
      "absolute_position": 5,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can AI make social engineering feel more personal or real?**\n\nThis lesson guides students to understand how AI is making social engineering attacks more scalable, convincing, and targeted. Through analyzing case studies and creating their own AI-generated scripts, students learn to identify different types of phishing and compare basic prevention strategies.",
        "preparation": "- Print copies of the Phishing Prevention Strategies Activity Guide (one for each student)",
        "student_overview": "**How can AI make social engineering feel more personal or real?**\n\nIn this lesson, you investigate how attackers use social engineering and artificial intelligence to create convincing scams like deepfakes and phishing attempts. You explore how these attacks work and learn strategies to identify and protect yourself from them."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-7",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "ai-powered-threats-and-defenses-pilot-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-8",
      "name": "Lesson 5: Successful Cybersecurity Stories",
      "absolute_position": 6,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can a cybersecurity defense protect users without them even realizing it?**\n\nThis lesson shifts focus from how systems fail to how they succeed. Students analyze real-world case studies of cyber threats that were stopped or mitigated by smart system design, human behavior, or AI tools. Through a jigsaw activity and class synthesis, they uncover what makes a cybersecurity defense effective, even when it’s invisible to the user.",
        "preparation": "- Print copies of the Defense in Action activity guide (one per student)\n- Print copies of the Case Studies (one case study per student)",
        "student_overview": "**How can a cybersecurity defense protect users without them even realizing it?**\n\nToday’s lesson explores real cybersecurity success stories where smart design, human action, or AI stopped a threat. By analyzing these examples, you get to see what makes a defense strong, even when no one notices it working."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-8",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "ai-powered-threats-and-defenses-pilot-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-9",
      "name": "Lesson 6: Confidentiality, Integrity, and Availability",
      "absolute_position": 7,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**What core security goals should you keep in mind when designing secure digital systems?**\n\nStudents explore common cybersecurity failures through relatable digital scenarios. By taking on the roles of attacker and defender, they examine how system flaws impact Confidentiality, Integrity, or Availability (CIA). They apply human-centered thinking to propose practical fixes and consider tradeoffs, laying the groundwork for deeper security concepts in upcoming lessons.",
        "preparation": "- Prepare copies of the Investigate a CIA Scenario: Cases handout (one per group)\n- Prepare copies of the Investigate a CIA Scenario: Attacker/Defender activity guide (one per group)",
        "student_overview": "**What core security goals should you keep in mind when designing secure digital systems?**\n\nThis activity focuses on real-life tech fails and how people can protect systems from harm. As both attacker and defender, you examine security issues and think through tradeoffs that affect users."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-9",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "ai-powered-threats-and-defenses-pilot-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-10",
      "name": "Lesson 7: Authentication, Authorization, and Accounting",
      "absolute_position": 8,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How do systems decide who you are and what you're allowed to do?**\n\nThis lesson introduces students to the AAA security framework—authentication, access control, and auditing—by focusing on the first two components through interactive stations. Students categorize authentication methods, explore how AI can exploit them, and design access control rules for real-world scenarios. The activities deepen students’ understanding of how systems verify identity and manage access while connecting those concepts to personal experiences.",
        "preparation": "- Print and cut out one full set of Access Control Scenario Cards for the entire class\n- Print and cut out a set of Authentication Method Cards (one copy per station)\n- Print out the Station Instruction Pages (pages 3-6 in the Station Setup and Instructions teacher resource)\n- Provide multiple sticky notes for each station",
        "student_overview": "**How do systems decide who you are and what you're allowed to do?**\n\nThis lesson introduces the AAA security model by exploring how systems check who you are and decide what you can access. Through hands-on activities, you sort authentication methods, spot potential weaknesses, and create access rules for real-world situations."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-10",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "ai-powered-threats-and-defenses-pilot-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-11",
      "name": "Lesson 8: AAA and AI",
      "absolute_position": 9,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**What role can AI play in enhancing AAA?**\n\nStudents investigate the \"Accounting\" component of AAA by analyzing user audit logs and comparing their findings to an AI chatbot’s results. They reflect on how context and identity influence human and machine judgments. The lesson then shifts to how AI is trained and used in adaptive authentication systems based on real-time risk.",
        "preparation": "- Print copies of the Fraud Detection Investigation Activity Guide (one copy per group)\n- Print copies of the four different user profiles",
        "student_overview": "**What role can AI play in enhancing AAA?**\n\nAnalyze suspicious activity in a user’s digital history and compare your thinking to an AI’s decisions. Explore how AI models learn and how authentication can change based on risk."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-11",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "ai-powered-threats-and-defenses-pilot-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-12",
      "name": "Lesson 9: Encryption",
      "absolute_position": 10,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**What makes encryption a powerful way to protect data?**\n\nThis lesson introduces encryption as a tool for protecting digital information by guiding students through the design of their own encryption method. Through hands-on exploration and comparison, students deepen their understanding of how symmetric and asymmetric encryption work and when each is used. The lesson concludes with a focus on how encryption protects data across different states — at rest, in transit, and in use — and the tradeoffs between security, speed, and usability.",
        "preparation": "- Print copies of the Encryption Design Challenge activity guide (one for each group of students)\n- (Optional) Print copies of the Design Challenge Inspiration Cards\n- (Optional) Print copies of the Caesar Cipher Wheel",
        "student_overview": "**What makes encryption a powerful way to protect data?**\n\nExplore how encryption keeps data safe by designing your own way to scramble a message. Compare your method to real-world encryption systems and learn how different types of encryption protect data when it’s stored, sent, or used."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-12",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "ai-powered-threats-and-defenses-pilot-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-13",
      "name": "Lesson 10: AI in Encryption",
      "absolute_position": 11,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How is AI reshaping what it means for data to be “secure” in encrypted systems?**\n\nThis lesson explores how artificial intelligence is reshaping the meaning of security in encrypted systems. Students examine how AI can crack weak passwords and make predictions about encrypted conversations by analyzing metadata. Through guided pattern-finding tasks and comparisons with AI-generated responses, students reflect on the role of AI in both protecting and challenging security. They end the lesson by choosing an AI-powered solution and weighing its potential benefits and tradeoffs.",
        "preparation": "- Print copies of the AI in Encryption activity guide (one for each student)",
        "student_overview": "**How is AI reshaping what it means for data to be “secure” in encrypted systems?**\n\nThis lesson explores how AI affects the way encrypted data is protected — or exposed. You’ll explore how AI can guess passwords and analyze message patterns to make predictions, even without reading what was said. Then, you’ll compare your thinking to AI’s and decide which security choices are worth the tradeoffs."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-13",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "ai-powered-threats-and-defenses-pilot-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-14",
      "name": "Lesson 11: Security vs Usability",
      "absolute_position": 12,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How do security and usability sometimes come into conflict?**\n\nThis lesson explores the tension between strong security and usable design through real-world case studies and a hands-on redesign challenge. Students take on the role of secure system designers, analyzing how security features impact users with different needs and proposing improvements that better balance protection and accessibility. The lesson emphasizes empathy, tradeoff reasoning, and inclusive design thinking.",
        "preparation": "- Print copies of the Redesign Challenge activity guide (one per group)\n- Print copies of the Security vs Usability Matrix handout (one per group)",
        "student_overview": "**How do security and usability sometimes come into conflict?**\n\nIn this lesson, you take on the role of a secure system designer, analyzing how security features affect real users and redesigning one to work better. You'll explore how strong protection can sometimes make technology harder to use—and how to find a better balance."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-14",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "ai-powered-threats-and-defenses-pilot-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-15",
      "name": "Lesson 12: Layered Defenses",
      "absolute_position": 13,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can several small defenses, stacked together, keep an everyday app safe and usable?**\n\nThis lesson guides students through exploring everyday security practices and applying the concept of **defense-in-depth**. Students identify security vulnerabilities within a sample system, tag them according to the **CIA triad** (Confidentiality, Integrity, Availability), and select layered defenses while staying within cost and friction constraints.",
        "preparation": "- Provide green, blue, and yellow colored pencils for students to use\n- Print copies of the Layered Defenses Activity Guide (one for each student)",
        "student_overview": "**How can several small defenses, stacked together, keep an everyday app safe and usable?**\n\nThrough hands-on mapping and reflective discussion, learn to balance usability with protection by stacking multiple security measures."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-15",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "ai-powered-threats-and-defenses-pilot-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-16",
      "name": "Lesson 13: Designing Secure Systems Project",
      "absolute_position": 14,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "In this unit’s final project, students investigate a real-world digital system by analyzing how different users experience potential risks and frustrations. Based on these user perspectives, students identify two distinct system issues—such as weak input validation or insecure data storage—and propose defense mechanism solutions for each. Students create a “Before” artifact that illustrates the original problems, and an “After” artifact that shows their redesigned solutions. Alongside the visual artifact, students explain how each fix works, what trade-offs it involves, and how it helps protect real users. The After artifact features a personified defense mechanism that communicates what it does and why it matters.",
        "preparation": "- Print copies of the AI Powered Threats and Defenses Project Guide (one for each pair of students)",
        "student_overview": "This project focuses on analyzing a real-world app to identify two security or usability issues that affect different users. The final product includes a Before-and-After artifact that shows a redesigned solution, along with a personified security feature that explains how it helps."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-16",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-4",
        "script.name": "ai-powered-threats-and-defenses-pilot-2025"
      }
    },
