    {
      "key": "4c1dc580-01b8-44d7-8a80-45d27831e2f7",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Student Survey"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4c1dc580-01b8-44d7-8a80-45d27831e2f7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "28326928-8272-44f6-a7fe-66b9d4b7cbc3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "de73a775-6c7f-4a83-8968-801f69d83eec",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullseye-arrow\"></i> **Goal of this activity:** Have students analyze an app through a user-centered design process that begins with them evaluating empathy maps.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to lead a stand-up/sit-down activity. Read each statement aloud one at a time. After each, pause so students can stand or stay seated. After all three, ask students to stay standing if they've ever used any of those things in a password.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use a neutral and light tone to keep the atmosphere safe and non-judgmental. If students seem hesitant, you can have them \"vote with fingers\" from their seats or do a silent poll by writing on paper or using an anonymous tool. The goal is reflection, not calling students out."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "de73a775-6c7f-4a83-8968-801f69d83eec",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2cdef66f-bc11-4778-857a-4ffda20545a7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "161465a0-9025-46da-ae6e-54965bf94753",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "161465a0-9025-46da-ae6e-54965bf94753",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2cdef66f-bc11-4778-857a-4ffda20545a7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "64ff2719-344b-4fd3-9755-eb17bd951bc1",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n- *What are the risks of sharing this kind of information online?*\n- *What might someone be able to do with that information?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should recognize that common behaviors like posting about birthdays, pets, or interests can reveal personal patterns. These patterns could be used by attackers to guess passwords or craft personalized messages — even if the posts seem harmless. Avoid directly naming terms like \"phishing\" or password attacks — let students surface those ideas themselves."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "64ff2719-344b-4fd3-9755-eb17bd951bc1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2cdef66f-bc11-4778-857a-4ffda20545a7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a742fbfb-02d7-458e-a0fe-6f5e73ab15bc",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Last lesson you learned how technical vulnerabilities can be exploited. Today, we'll explore how attackers target human behavior and how those vulnerabilities can make even secure systems break down.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a742fbfb-02d7-458e-a0fe-6f5e73ab15bc",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2cdef66f-bc11-4778-857a-4ffda20545a7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d65ba06b-ad77-4b45-ba2e-0055a092de02",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d65ba06b-ad77-4b45-ba2e-0055a092de02",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2cdef66f-bc11-4778-857a-4ffda20545a7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4f309072-2046-497c-b0fc-7ef158d33501",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullseye-arrow\"></i> **Goal of this activity:** Students analyze how phishing messages exploit predictable human behavior and emotions to gain trust. They examine how attackers personalize scams using publicly shared personal information to make them more believable.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students take out their AI Powered Threat and Defenses Unit Guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define attacks. Explain that attacks can take many forms, but they all involve trying to disrupt systems or access things without permission. Tell students they'll be learning about attacks that target people — not just systems — in today's lesson.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define phishing. Emphasize that phishing targets human behaviors — not just technology — by tricking people into giving away personal information.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Briefly explain that attackers now use AI tools to create phishing messages that are harder to spot. AI can pull together personal information to make messages feel more real, and it can also scale up attacks by generating tons of slightly different versions quickly.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Phishing"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4f309072-2046-497c-b0fc-7ef158d33501",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f175f905-8110-461c-a9ad-5e87b1db9503"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0b76135b-04d7-4148-9183-105ba6039e39",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Imagine you're getting dozens of emails a day — one of them feels like it was written just for you. That's what AI can do for a scammer. As we look at our user's messages today, keep in mind: which ones might seem \"too personal,\" or \"too perfect\"? Could AI be behind that?",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0b76135b-04d7-4148-9183-105ba6039e39",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f175f905-8110-461c-a9ad-5e87b1db9503"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6f41fc83-b5bb-4529-ba0b-22d37aa902f9",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a copy of the Hackable Human activity guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 3, Levels 1-3 to have students work through the phishing investigation for a chosen persona.\n- **Level 1:** Students select a fictional user and identify what they’ve posted online.\n- **Level 2:** Students review messages sent to that persona and decide which seem real or suspicious.\n- **Level 3:** Students use AI Chat to reflect on whether they were right and what clues made each message believable or manipulative.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Ask students what clues they're using to decide whether a message is real or fake. Encourage them to look for patterns like urgency, emotional appeals, too-good-to-be-true rewards, or overly personal details. Push students to explain their thinking, not just guess.",
        "progression_name": "Phishing Investigation",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If students struggle to decide whether a message is phishing, encourage them to look at tone and context. Phishing often sounds urgent, suspiciously generous, or weirdly personal. Remind students it’s okay to be unsure — the goal is to explain their reasoning, not just get the “right” answer."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6f41fc83-b5bb-4529-ba0b-22d37aa902f9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f175f905-8110-461c-a9ad-5e87b1db9503"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "79d2e02e-d5cf-46f2-8775-638fece95858",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "79d2e02e-d5cf-46f2-8775-638fece95858",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f175f905-8110-461c-a9ad-5e87b1db9503"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5a20f59a-c0fe-405f-a39e-9e65bee2ce4b",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What makes phishing messages so convincing and how does human behavior play a role?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should recognize that phishing attacks succeed by mimicking familiar or emotional messages and exploiting predictable behaviors — like posting personal information or responding quickly without thinking. This prepares them to spot similar patterns in password-related attacks.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "Use this discussion to assess students' understanding of how phishing messages exploit human behaviors and emotions. Look for students identifying tactics like urgency, emotional appeals, or personal targeting — and connecting them to behaviors like oversharing, habit-based clicking, or trusting familiar formats.\nIf students focus only on the appearance of the message (e.g., logos or typos), push them to consider why someone might fall for it — and how attackers use that to their advantage. Consider capturing key student takeaways as anchor ideas for the password attack discussion that follows."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5a20f59a-c0fe-405f-a39e-9e65bee2ce4b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f175f905-8110-461c-a9ad-5e87b1db9503"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a4bbca7e-e55a-4040-8f4b-cdf16c790701",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a4bbca7e-e55a-4040-8f4b-cdf16c790701",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f175f905-8110-461c-a9ad-5e87b1db9503"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ac7b8972-895f-4988-82e7-92433b69779f",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullseye-arrow\"></i> **Goal of this activity:** Students investigate a simulated account breach and analyze how predictable human behavior — like password reuse or oversharing — can make people vulnerable to identity-based attacks like guessing or credential stuffing.",
        "duration": "20",
        "name": "Password Attacks"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ac7b8972-895f-4988-82e7-92433b69779f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f175f905-8110-461c-a9ad-5e87b1db9503"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e1ede798-5513-4696-9589-35060f8acba6",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Imagine your user's account from earlier actually got hacked. You're now on the security response team. Your job is to figure out what happened and how the attacker might have broken in.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e1ede798-5513-4696-9589-35060f8acba6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f175f905-8110-461c-a9ad-5e87b1db9503"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "cdc07218-2b03-4897-b495-d154e1a8d98c",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 3, Levels 4 to act as security response team members and try to figure out which password attack was used on their fictional persona.",
        "progression_name": "Breach Reports"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "cdc07218-2b03-4897-b495-d154e1a8d98c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f175f905-8110-461c-a9ad-5e87b1db9503"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "cbc1f160-ce47-476a-a23d-20fb89030a14",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Ask students what clues from the breach report helped them identify the attack. Look for connections to weak or reused passwords, predictable personal info, or signs of automation. Encourage students to use evidence to explain their reasoning.\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Some students may jump to conclusions based on the password alone. Encourage them to consider all clues in the breach report — like number of login attempts, use of automation, or repeated patterns — before deciding which attack was used."
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "Use student responses in the activity guide — especially the phishing message analysis, AI chat reflection, and breach report investigation — as a formative check of the lesson objectives.\n- If students are unsure about what makes a message believable or manipulative, revisit examples from Level 2 together. Encourage them to look for emotional triggers, urgency, tone, or overly personal details.\n- If students can’t explain how human behavior contributed to the password breach, model how oversharing, password reuse, or predictable choices can lead to vulnerabilities.\n- If students identify the attack type correctly but struggle to explain why, prompt them to look back at specific clues in the breach report (e.g., number of attempts, timing, reused credentials, automation).\n- Consider doing a quick class debrief or peer-share to surface key patterns — especially if many students chose different personas and encountered different types of attacks."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "cbc1f160-ce47-476a-a23d-20fb89030a14",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f175f905-8110-461c-a9ad-5e87b1db9503"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8f6388ee-0572-4482-be50-6da7a53ba512",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8f6388ee-0572-4482-be50-6da7a53ba512",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f175f905-8110-461c-a9ad-5e87b1db9503"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b0777af6-6a87-4600-aeb3-2f318fc35c5d",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Use the blue play icon to start the Give One, Get One activity. Prompt students to find a partner and share what password attack was used on their fictional user — and how the attacker got in. After both students share, they should find a new partner and repeat the process. After the activity, invite students to revise their activity guide if they learned something new from a peer.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Using music to cue transitions helps build predictable routines. Let students know what the music means and be consistent in using it to launch this type of activity. Click the blue play icon on the slide to begin.\n\nGive One, Get One encourages students to circulate and share their findings. Each student “gives” an idea to a partner, then “gets” an idea in return. Prompt students to repeat with new partners, and encourage them to listen for unfamiliar attack types or details they missed."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b0777af6-6a87-4600-aeb3-2f318fc35c5d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f175f905-8110-461c-a9ad-5e87b1db9503"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4bc80e32-4a9d-4323-92e9-d992e6bf287c",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4bc80e32-4a9d-4323-92e9-d992e6bf287c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f175f905-8110-461c-a9ad-5e87b1db9503"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b7bb3f81-071b-4017-bedf-c5deac668ea7",
      "position": 14,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What did all the password attacks have in common and what made them different?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should recognize that while the tactics varied (guessing, spraying, stuffing, brute force), the root causes often involved predictable human behavior — weak passwords, personal info, and password reuse. This reflection prepares them to reflect on the Question of the Day by helping them identify shared patterns across all four types of attacks and how human behavior plays a role.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "Use this discussion to check whether students can recognize shared patterns across different password attack types. Listen for understanding of human vulnerabilities — like weak passwords, password reuse, and predictable choices — and how those contributed to the success of different attacks.\nIf students name the correct attack types but struggle to explain why, refer them back to their breach reports for evidence. Consider having students write a 1–2 sentence takeaway afterward to summarize what they learned about human behavior across the different attack types."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b7bb3f81-071b-4017-bedf-c5deac668ea7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f175f905-8110-461c-a9ad-5e87b1db9503"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "517617aa-6830-419c-a993-eaf7446c8027",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Facilitate a Think-Write-Share around the Question of the Day: \"How do cyber attacks exploit human vulnerabilities, i.e. trust, emotion, and predictable behavior?\"\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Key Vocabulary.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 3, Level 5 to complete the End of Lesson Survey."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "517617aa-6830-419c-a993-eaf7446c8027",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5a5ed889-5864-481a-914b-3914b3674506"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0f615e94-12a0-42a0-9cd7-6455dfdfba51",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Student Survey"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0f615e94-12a0-42a0-9cd7-6455dfdfba51",
        "lesson_activity.key": "741d0b58-4f49-4413-a174-c8634bba94f5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "57409bf8-0288-4462-b40a-7d15b501cd16",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-video-camera\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Video:** Show the \"Social Engineering Hacker\" video.\n**Questions to consider with the video:** \n- How did the woman calling the phone company get the information that she wanted?\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should identify and highlight the various social engineering tactics the woman used to manipulate the phone company into giving her access to the account. Examples may include claiming it was her husband's account, using a fake crying baby in the background to create urgency and sympathy, and sounding distressed or emotional to lower the guard of the customer service rep. The goal is for students to recognize how simple manipulative techniques can trick people into giving up sensitive information or taking unintended actions, which is a major concern in cybersecurity.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review three common social engineering tactics. Use the corresponding clips from the Social Engineering Hacker video to illustrate each tactic in the earlier phone call example."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "57409bf8-0288-4462-b40a-7d15b501cd16",
        "lesson_activity.key": "88683747-5f33-4faf-94ac-b0c8aef98ccc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "41e78b9c-4205-4ccb-b95f-61caadccacd1",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "As we just saw, social engineering relies on tricking people rather than hacking machines. In today's lesson, we'll look more closely at how attackers use deception, especially with the help of AI, to make these scams more convincing, and what we can do to protect ourselves.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "41e78b9c-4205-4ccb-b95f-61caadccacd1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "88683747-5f33-4faf-94ac-b0c8aef98ccc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3499a96a-fcfb-44fe-a1af-224ab7f4208d",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3499a96a-fcfb-44fe-a1af-224ab7f4208d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "88683747-5f33-4faf-94ac-b0c8aef98ccc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "31c20600-2f2a-4d68-b666-267a060fbc7b",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students take out their AI Powered Threat and Defenses Unit Guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 4, Level 1 to complete Levels 1 through 3.\n- **Level 1:** Students learn about smishing and answer questions about a real-world example they found in their unit guide.\n- **Level 2:** Students learn about vishing and answer questions about a real-world example they found in their unit guide.\n- **Level 3:** Students learn about deepfake video impersonations and answer questions about a real-world example they found in their unit guide.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Investigation of AI-Powered Phishing Scams",
        "progression_name": "Phishing Scams",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If students encounter paywalls or blocked content, encourage them to search for the specific topic they’re exploring. For example, if they find a story about a smishing incident but can’t access the first few links, have them search for that specific case using keywords like: “White House Chief of Staff smishing incident”. This can help them find more accessible articles or videos on the same topic."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "31c20600-2f2a-4d68-b666-267a060fbc7b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c2c740d9-3334-44c1-820f-2691bbf28f21"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b5941b0d-95de-4b2e-a351-e915988f1c44",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b5941b0d-95de-4b2e-a351-e915988f1c44",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c2c740d9-3334-44c1-820f-2691bbf28f21"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f3519338-c379-4390-961f-a091b751f0a5",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** For each phishing scam, have one student share-out a real-world examples they found with the whole class.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *social engineering*.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What do you think smishing and vishing are based on what you've learned so far?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students will infer the meanings of smishing and vishing by connecting them to phishing. They may recall from earlier warm-up examples that phishing can happen in different formats, and from the previous activity, they may remember that smishing occurs over text messages (SMS) and vishing happens through voice calls.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *smishing*.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *vishing*.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define deepfake."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f3519338-c379-4390-961f-a091b751f0a5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c2c740d9-3334-44c1-820f-2691bbf28f21"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f1fd6984-fce6-4e95-a2aa-96c9f5d9356f",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Lesson 4, Level 4. Students will use AI Chat to create a phishing phone call or video script using the voice of a chosen persona, such as a celebrity, family member, or school staff member. They should provide a quote or writing sample to help AI match the voice, then guide the AI to craft a message convincing someone to send money, click a link, or download a file. Encourage them to include persuasive tactics like emotion, urgency, or authority, and to refine their script through at least three AI interactions.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Create a Deep Fake Script",
        "progression_name": "Create a Deep Fake Script",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "AI Chat will not generate a phishing text, email, or script if the word \"phishing\" is used. Instead, have students describe what it is they want AI to help them generate, for example:\n- Create a 1 minute video script in the voice of this musical artist encouraging fans to click on a link\n- Create a 30 second voicemail in the style of a teacher urging a parent to call a specific phone number and follow the prompts"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f1fd6984-fce6-4e95-a2aa-96c9f5d9356f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c2c740d9-3334-44c1-820f-2691bbf28f21"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2b7ee9a6-3f31-415c-aecd-32ae3dc41477",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2b7ee9a6-3f31-415c-aecd-32ae3dc41477",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c2c740d9-3334-44c1-820f-2691bbf28f21"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "03f3568b-7cf4-4805-8d3b-9e7f6f540213",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Give each student a copy of the Phishing Prevention Strategies activity guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students swap scripts with their partner. In their activity guide,  provide an action someone could take to determine if the video/call is legitimate or a phishing attempt for questions that apply.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Lesson 4, Level 5 to respond to the free-response questions.",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If time permits, use the View Student Responses to run a brief discussion asking students to compare the strategies they came up with on Level 5."
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "Use both the free-response level and the class discussion to formatively assess the lesson objectives. Look for evidence that students:\n- Recognize manipulation strategies in the scripts\n- Connect red flags to appropriate prevention actions\n- Thoughtfully evaluate which defenses are most effective and why\n\nIf students struggle:\n- Model one example as a class, highlighting which strategies apply and why they matter\n- Have students revisit the phishing red flag checklist and choose one strategy to focus on improving\n- Use the extension prompt to deepen analysis, such as categorizing strategies as technical or behavioral"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "03f3568b-7cf4-4805-8d3b-9e7f6f540213",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c2c740d9-3334-44c1-820f-2691bbf28f21"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4e9c011c-7352-4dd0-8e77-a3de8eb1867f",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Key Vocabulary.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 4, Level 6 to complete the End of Lesson Survey.",
        "progression_name": "Student Survey"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4e9c011c-7352-4dd0-8e77-a3de8eb1867f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c051bf52-994d-4a17-a0ef-9d28364582a6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "bccbe08a-b88c-4733-9a9e-9a30d2f02950",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullseye-arrow\"></i> **Goal of this activity:** Get students thinking about familiar digital experiences that are actually security features, and spark curiosity about how defenses work behind the scenes.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Display the two common security features, CAPTCHA and one-time passcode (OTP). Ask students to raise their hands if they have seen either of them before and to keep their hand up if they knew either one of them was protecting them somehow. Then, briefly explain what each one does:\n- CAPTCHA is designed to tell whether you're a real person or a bot. It protects websites from fake signups and spam attacks.\n- OTP (One-Time Passcode) adds an extra step when you log in. Even if someone steals your password, they still can't get in without the special code.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click the animated slide to display the prompts.\n- *Which security feature do you think most people ignore or overlook, and why?*\n- *What makes it more important than it might seem at first?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students recognize that common digital security features, like CAPTCHA and OTP, are designed to quietly protect users from serious threats. This discussion helps shift their perspective from seeing these tools as annoying or unimportant to understanding their real value in keeping systems and people safe.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Keep this discussion light and conversational as students may not have thought of these as \"cyber defenses\" before, so validating their experience builds confidence for the case studies coming up."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "bccbe08a-b88c-4733-9a9e-9a30d2f02950",
        "lesson_activity.key": "6ee8166b-345b-45aa-b671-8998b5962988"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8b175251-d266-4dad-9083-f17751b6e5ab",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8b175251-d266-4dad-9083-f17751b6e5ab",
        "lesson_activity.key": "6ee8166b-345b-45aa-b671-8998b5962988"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "196910d4-6527-4090-9178-3e7c19a07170",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "196910d4-6527-4090-9178-3e7c19a07170",
        "lesson_activity.key": "6ee8166b-345b-45aa-b671-8998b5962988"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e56742da-7475-4892-8ade-9caba1a1998c",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullseye-arrow\"></i> **Goal of this activity:** Help students analyze real-world cybersecurity defenses using reasoning and system thinking.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students take out their AI Powered Threat and Defenses Unit Guide.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Expert Group Investigation"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e56742da-7475-4892-8ade-9caba1a1998c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7c0b6d8d-f0dd-4226-9728-59236c54243a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a3d27e0c-a9b0-4eb9-ace9-0ec85404c478",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We just looked at some common digital features, like login alerts, CAPTCHA, or password reset links, that quietly protect us every day. Even if they feel annoying, they’re actually working behind the scenes to keep our information safe. In cybersecurity, those kinds of protections are called defense mechanisms. They can be built into the system, powered by AI, or even come from people noticing when something's not right.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a3d27e0c-a9b0-4eb9-ace9-0ec85404c478",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7c0b6d8d-f0dd-4226-9728-59236c54243a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "09a443ee-51e7-4969-a2af-7a7b86573a22",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *defense mechanisms*.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Place students in groups of three to four.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a copy of the Defense in Action activity guide and a Case Study.",
        "progression_name": "Defense in Action Activity Guide"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "09a443ee-51e7-4969-a2af-7a7b86573a22",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7c0b6d8d-f0dd-4226-9728-59236c54243a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a5fd625a-18c8-480f-9bab-7046ea696c4f",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to gather with three other classmates who have the same case study and go through it together. Explain the task for this first part is to read and discuss the case study with their group and work together to fill out the activity guide about the threat, the response, and what was protected. Encourage students to reason through how human behavior, system design, or AI played a role.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If groups are stuck identifying the technical defense, suggest one of the these prompts to help them:\n- What stopped the attacker? What is timing? A person? A tool?\n- Was there something built into the system (e.g. expired link, more than one way to identify the user, etc)?\n- Would this still work if no one reported the attack?"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a5fd625a-18c8-480f-9bab-7046ea696c4f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7c0b6d8d-f0dd-4226-9728-59236c54243a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "cafde9ab-00b2-43e4-82fc-f63679802542",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "cafde9ab-00b2-43e4-82fc-f63679802542",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7c0b6d8d-f0dd-4226-9728-59236c54243a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "676075bd-439a-4483-84c8-cd4a16fdc7c3",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullseye-arrow\"></i> **Goal of this activity:** Synthesize similarities and differences across defense cases to build student understanding of layered defense and roles of AI, design, and human action.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Regroup students into new jigsaw teams with one member from each original expert group. Each student shares their case study. As a group, they compare:\n- What kinds of threats did we see?\n- What kinds of defenses showed up across stories?\n- What role did people play vs. the system or AI?\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** As students share, listen for misconceptions such as assuming AI always works or ignoring human behavior in the defense.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click the animated slide to display the prompts.\n- *What do most successful defenses seem to include?*\n- *When did human behavior make the difference?*\n- *When did AI or smart system design catch something people might miss?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should recognize that strong defenses often include a combination of smart system design, active human participation, and even AI, and that depending on only one layer can leave gaps.",
        "duration": "20",
        "name": "Jigsaw Share-Outs",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The activity guide can be collected and used to formatively assess student understanding of the lesson objectives."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "676075bd-439a-4483-84c8-cd4a16fdc7c3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7c0b6d8d-f0dd-4226-9728-59236c54243a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "723ccbd2-545e-484b-83c0-3a9c851f91ab",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "723ccbd2-545e-484b-83c0-3a9c851f91ab",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7c0b6d8d-f0dd-4226-9728-59236c54243a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "00d16041-80e5-4e82-8af0-84ba6a20acfa",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 5, Level 2 to complete the Check for Understanding question.",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The free response level can be used as a formative assessment of the lesson objectives:\n- Explain how system design, human behavior, and AI can work together to prevent a cyber threat.\n- Evaluate different defenses to determine what made them effective.\n\nAs students submit their responses, teachers can circulate and provide quick feedback by:\n- Looking for clear and accurate descriptions of:\n  - What type of threat was involved\n  - Who or what stopped it (human, system, or AI)\n  - Why the defense worked (and what could’ve gone wrong without it)\n- Asking probing questions like:\n  - \"How did human action support or fail the defense here?\"\n  - \"Would this defense have worked without AI or without the system?\"\n  - \"What makes this defense effective even if users don't notice it?\"\n\nTeachers can also provide written feedback through the Free Response level, prompting students to clarify:\n- Which part of the defense was most important\n- How different roles (human, AI, system) worked together\n- Whether their example shows a layered defense or a single point of failure"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "00d16041-80e5-4e82-8af0-84ba6a20acfa",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7c0b6d8d-f0dd-4226-9728-59236c54243a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "85adaf74-fd44-4974-8703-d395bf54344f",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students respond to the Question of the Day in their Unit Guide. Then, direct students to pair up with their neighbor and share their answers. Have partners add one follow-up thought or reaction to their partner's response.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Key Vocabulary."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "85adaf74-fd44-4974-8703-d395bf54344f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a5bc1f3b-08d8-4915-bf0f-bb2d5c939489"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0d2f7030-3f78-4de3-a060-85345d66cebd",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Student Survey"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0d2f7030-3f78-4de3-a060-85345d66cebd",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a5bc1f3b-08d8-4915-bf0f-bb2d5c939489"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a3c1dcf1-41d7-43b0-af42-ee63b13a663c",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullseye-arrow\"></i> **Goal of this activity:** Activate students' instincts around what makes digital actions or platforms feel risky or safe, as a lead-in to discussing how systems protect data and users.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Let students know that the next few slides will each show a short tech scenario. For each one, they should decide how much they trust it, and respond by holding up a thumbs up, thumbs down, or thumbs sideways.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If time allows, consider having students move to different parts of the room or place themselves along a spectrum line to show how risky or trustworthy each situation feels to them."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a3c1dcf1-41d7-43b0-af42-ee63b13a663c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e9a90ee8-ede0-4d90-bbf7-8d0adce2a2f0"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "eea3a615-5f23-4852-bb88-b358290fa828",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "eea3a615-5f23-4852-bb88-b358290fa828",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e9a90ee8-ede0-4d90-bbf7-8d0adce2a2f0"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e8bea997-a684-42fe-9406-e9c44ea900aa",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Read Scenario #1 aloud, then ask students to respond with thumbs up, down, or sideways.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Read Scenario #2 aloud, then ask students to respond with thumbs up, down, or sideways.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Read Scenario #3 aloud, then ask students to respond with thumbs up, down, or sideways.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What made something feel untrustworthy? Was it about privacy, accuracy, or access?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Help students realize that trust in digital tools depends on three big things: privacy, accuracy, and access. Listen for students mentioning things like:\n- \"What if someone sees my stuff?\" (previews Confidentiality)\n- \"What if someone changes it or messes it up?\" (previews Integrity)\n- \"What if I can't use it when I need it?\" (previews Availability)\n\nEncourage students to connect their instincts to real consequences: frustration, embarrassment, missed deadlines, etc. This helps them build empathy and sets up the need for systems that protect people from those harms.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If students are unsure, model your reasoning out loud: \"I wouldn't trust public Wi-Fi because I don’t know who else is on the network. What if they could see what I'm doing?” Remind students there are no wrong answers! They're sharing instincts, not technical definitions."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e8bea997-a684-42fe-9406-e9c44ea900aa",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e9a90ee8-ede0-4d90-bbf7-8d0adce2a2f0"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8b934a7a-beee-42bf-8571-a681ea8eb2ba",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8b934a7a-beee-42bf-8571-a681ea8eb2ba",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e9a90ee8-ede0-4d90-bbf7-8d0adce2a2f0"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "40d3631f-c5ea-4b0c-b7a2-c826bbd49e75",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "All these situations you just reacted to, they might seem different, but they all boil down to the same idea: something could go wrong. You could lose privacy, lose control of your stuff, or lose access to it. In cybersecurity, those are the three big risks we try to prevent. We call them Confidentiality, Integrity, and Availability. Let's take a look at what each one means.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "40d3631f-c5ea-4b0c-b7a2-c826bbd49e75",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e9a90ee8-ede0-4d90-bbf7-8d0adce2a2f0"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "18c3b3c7-7fe9-4edd-b287-3053a952e511",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "18c3b3c7-7fe9-4edd-b287-3053a952e511",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e9a90ee8-ede0-4d90-bbf7-8d0adce2a2f0"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "03f08ca5-48d5-48f4-8dc4-0a1def3ad512",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullseye-arrow\"></i> **Goal of this activity:** Introduce the three terms: Confidentiality, Integrity, Availability and ensure students understand the differences and nuances between the different pillars.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students take out their AI Powered Threat and Defenses Unit Guide.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "What is the CIA Triad?"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "03f08ca5-48d5-48f4-8dc4-0a1def3ad512",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2b6b9108-1e62-4377-82f4-0ba5e7fdebce"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d5f2c8ef-8f04-40f0-b7ce-6e77c0998b0c",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "All those situations we just looked at — they might seem really different, but they all point to the same risks. You could lose privacy, lose control of your stuff, or lose access to it. In cybersecurity, those are the three big things we try to protect. We call them Confidentiality, Integrity, and Availability, or the CIA Triad.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d5f2c8ef-8f04-40f0-b7ce-6e77c0998b0c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2b6b9108-1e62-4377-82f4-0ba5e7fdebce"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5c67e9a8-5211-4b64-bd33-f09f423e9282",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *CIA Triad*. Let students know these three goals help professionals understand what went wrong in a system and how to protect people from harm.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Write \"Confidentiality\", \"Integrity\", and \"Availability\" on the board as visible anchors for the rest of the lesson."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5c67e9a8-5211-4b64-bd33-f09f423e9282",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2b6b9108-1e62-4377-82f4-0ba5e7fdebce"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0191c6d0-2dcc-4aca-9d7d-e2a505995516",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0191c6d0-2dcc-4aca-9d7d-e2a505995516",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2b6b9108-1e62-4377-82f4-0ba5e7fdebce"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1b029050-04e8-4237-8586-9b5a6f326b28",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *Confidentiality*. Give real-life examples students can relate to, like private messages, saved passwords, or medical info.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *Integrity*. Use relatable examples, like when someone messes with a shared doc or changes a score without permission.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *Availability*. Use relatable examples of times when a system didn’t work, like during testing, due dates, or app failures.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that you will read a short scenario out loud, then students must decide which part of the CIA Triad it fits (Confidentiality, Integrity, or Availability) and move to that labeled area in the room.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If time or space is limited, students can do a quick turn-and-talk or hold up an index card labeled C, I, or A instead of moving. The goal is to to get students talking and distinguishing between the categories and quickly check for understanding and clarify any questions student may have."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1b029050-04e8-4237-8586-9b5a6f326b28",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2b6b9108-1e62-4377-82f4-0ba5e7fdebce"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "78da7252-20d7-4e3d-b9e1-6e63c44a18f0",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "78da7252-20d7-4e3d-b9e1-6e63c44a18f0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2b6b9108-1e62-4377-82f4-0ba5e7fdebce"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "72e8d240-7551-478b-b600-0e9d9eb19e2c",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Read the scenario aloud. Have students move to the side of the room labeled \"Confidentiality\", \"Integrity\", or \"Availability\" based on what they believe the scenario represents. Ask a few volunteers from each group to explain their reasoning before revealing the answer: Availability – the system wasn't accessible when needed, leading to a missed deadline.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Read the scenario aloud. Have students move to the side of the room labeled \"Confidentiality\", \"Integrity\", or \"Availability\" based on what they believe the scenario represents. Ask a few volunteers from each group to explain their reasoning before revealing the answer:  Confidentiality — sensitive personal information was visible to people it wasn't intended for.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Read the scenario aloud. Have students move to the side of the room labeled \"Confidentiality\", \"Integrity\", or \"Availability\" based on what they believe the scenario represents. Ask a few volunteers from each group to explain their reasoning before revealing the answer: Integrity — the file was tampered with and is no longer what the author intended.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Read the scenario aloud. Have students move to the side of the room labeled \"Confidentiality\", \"Integrity\", or \"Availability\" based on what they believe the scenario represents. Ask a few volunteers from each group to explain their reasoning before revealing the answer: Integrity and Confidentiality — the playlist was altered without permission (Integrity), and her listening habits were visible and changed by someone else (Confidentiality)."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "72e8d240-7551-478b-b600-0e9d9eb19e2c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2b6b9108-1e62-4377-82f4-0ba5e7fdebce"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6b5286c0-6148-4768-823a-43e9ebc4232c",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullseye-arrow\"></i> Goal of this activity:  Students take turns roleplaying attackers and defenders to analyze system failures and apply the CIA Triad. They propose simple fixes and think through tradeoffs, practicing how cybersecurity pros protect people.",
        "duration": "20",
        "name": "Investigate a CIA Scenario"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6b5286c0-6148-4768-823a-43e9ebc4232c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2b6b9108-1e62-4377-82f4-0ba5e7fdebce"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8d2af9fc-68eb-4145-be65-1dbaa3b04f3a",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Now that we better understand the different pillars of the CIA Triad, let's take it a step further. In this next activity, you and your partner will explore real-world system failures from two angles: as an attacker looking for weaknesses in the CIA of a system, and as a defender figuring out how to stop the attack or reduce the damage.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8d2af9fc-68eb-4145-be65-1dbaa3b04f3a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2b6b9108-1e62-4377-82f4-0ba5e7fdebce"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "fb6e4bca-c8a8-49dd-b0aa-3fdcd242e26d",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each pair of students a copy of the Attacker/Defender activity guide and Scenario Descriptions handout.",
        "progression_name": "Attack/Defender Activity Guide"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "fb6e4bca-c8a8-49dd-b0aa-3fdcd242e26d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2b6b9108-1e62-4377-82f4-0ba5e7fdebce"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "57d75a28-ec59-4134-a288-1528afc4dae4",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the steps with students. Emphasize the two roles, attacker and defender, and their goals. Let students know they'll rotate through 6 case files. Each time, they identify the CIA failure, explain why it matters, pick a fix, and consider the tradeoff.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Let students know that not every cybersecurity failure comes from a \"hacker\". Sometimes regular users accidentally cause problems because the system didn’t have the right protections in place. In this activity, even if the \"attacker\" didn't mean to cause harm, the goal is still to analyze what went wrong or could go wrong and how it could be prevented."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "57d75a28-ec59-4134-a288-1528afc4dae4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2b6b9108-1e62-4377-82f4-0ba5e7fdebce"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a336fdf3-4810-4700-af76-f3402cf7a7ec",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a336fdf3-4810-4700-af76-f3402cf7a7ec",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2b6b9108-1e62-4377-82f4-0ba5e7fdebce"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6045adb4-95c0-449a-ac0d-2533184132a4",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Read the example scenario on the slide and have students look at the activity guide table but not to fill it out yet, this is just an example. Also have them look at the Solution Bank and Tradeoff Bank on the back of their Scenario handout.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Walk students through how to fill in each column in the table using the example on the slide. Use this to show what kind of thinking goes into attacker/defender responses. Emphasize that there isn't always just one right answer; there can be multiple reasonable fixes and tradeoffs."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6045adb4-95c0-449a-ac0d-2533184132a4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2b6b9108-1e62-4377-82f4-0ba5e7fdebce"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "783af694-fb25-4fbe-8cb2-d84bc2186ef6",
      "position": 14,
      "properties": {
        "description": "In this case, the attacker saw private messages — that's a confidentiality failure. The student might not even know it happened until it's too late. It matters because private information was exposed or an attacker could impersonate or harass them. A good fix might be requiring two-step verification or strong authentication to prove it's really you. But that might take longer to log in or frustrate users who aren't tech-savvy.",
        "remarks": true,
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If time allows, consider projecting a blank activity guide table for this example and asking students to suggest what goes in each column. Fill in the table live as students contribute. If a suggestion is off, gently redirect by asking:\n- \"Does that really show what the attacker could see, change, or block?\"\n- \"Would that fix actually stop the attacker, or is it too generic\"\n\nThis approach helps surface common misunderstandings and builds confidence in applying the framework."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "783af694-fb25-4fbe-8cb2-d84bc2186ef6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2b6b9108-1e62-4377-82f4-0ba5e7fdebce"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e4c5d1ed-304b-4e6f-979a-861828a1bb43",
      "position": 15,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e4c5d1ed-304b-4e6f-979a-861828a1bb43",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2b6b9108-1e62-4377-82f4-0ba5e7fdebce"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "76c70103-00a8-4b7a-b92a-ebb6a1f039a3",
      "position": 16,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Let students know that if they're unsure what to write in a column or how to determine a fix to a problem, there are supports available. These include the Solution Bank and Tradeoff Bank found on the back of their Scenario handout, as well as AI Chat in Level 2.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage students to try explaining their thinking to a partner before jumping to the support tools. Sometimes, talking it through helps clarify their ideas."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "76c70103-00a8-4b7a-b92a-ebb6a1f039a3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2b6b9108-1e62-4377-82f4-0ba5e7fdebce"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3b768250-6e2c-4ceb-910f-2e8fadd1d360",
      "position": 17,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3b768250-6e2c-4ceb-910f-2e8fadd1d360",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2b6b9108-1e62-4377-82f4-0ba5e7fdebce"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ca20cd9f-83b6-4e8e-86ac-2b3b24d36263",
      "position": 18,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Instruct students that they'll now begin working through their scenarios. They should rotate roles with each one and complete their activity guide as they go. Reinforce that they should be discussing why the fix helps and what the tradeoff is, not just copy something down. Remind students know that if they need support, they can use the Solution Bank and Tradeoff Bank on the back of the Scenario handout. They also have the option to use AI Chat on Level 2 to help them figure out which pillar is affected, why it matters, potential solutions, and tradeoffs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** As students move through their scenarios, listen for mix-ups in the CIA pillars, unclear attacker logic, or vague fixes. Ask questions to help them be specific:\n- \"What did the attacker actually do?\"\n- \"What part of the system failed?\"\n- \"How does your fix stop it?\"\n",
        "progression_name": "AI Chat: Investigate a CIA Scenario",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If they're unsure what the attacker would do, offer cues: seeing something private = confidentiality, changing something = integrity, blocking access = availability. Encourage realistic examples, like reading messages or flooding a system. For defenders who pick a fix without thinking, ask:\n- \"What does the fix actually do?\"\n- \"Would it block, prevent, or monitor something?\"\n\nIf time allows, have pairs compare responses. Prompt them to look for what kinds of fixes worked best and where tradeoffs came up. You can point out how this links to next class topics like authentication and access control."
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Investigate a CIA Scenario activity guide can be collected and used to check if students identified the right pillar, explained the failure clearly, chose a reasonable fix, and thought about tradeoffs. If needed, review a scenario together and model how to break it down."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ca20cd9f-83b6-4e8e-86ac-2b3b24d36263",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2b6b9108-1e62-4377-82f4-0ba5e7fdebce"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1136f2f9-1ac9-4012-9538-b6f042fb6f0c",
      "position": 19,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Now that you've seen what can go wrong in a system, let's look at the professionals who work behind the scenes to prevent those failures and what happens when those jobs aren't done well.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1136f2f9-1ac9-4012-9538-b6f042fb6f0c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2b6b9108-1e62-4377-82f4-0ba5e7fdebce"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "19302ea8-c2e4-4318-b0ea-9149dd54f386",
      "position": 20,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students go Lesson 6, Level 3 to explore careers that deal with the CIA Triad. They should complete the free response question on Level 4 once they've completed the review of careers.",
        "progression_name": "CIA Careers",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If time allows, use the View Student Responses to run a discussion based on student responses to the question on Level 4: \"Which career do you think makes the biggest difference? Why?\" Encourage students to use reasoning tied to the CIA Triad: \"This job helps make sure systems stay available\" or \"This one stops private info from leaking.\" Push them to think beyond job titles and into the impact of the work."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "19302ea8-c2e4-4318-b0ea-9149dd54f386",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2b6b9108-1e62-4377-82f4-0ba5e7fdebce"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f880acef-8db3-4c3f-9ff3-a47f373502e3",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Give students a minute to write down their answer to the Question of the Day in their Unit Guide. Then, have students raise their hands and shout out a word or phrase (e.g., \"keep data private!\" or \"make sure people can access stuff!\"). As students are shouting out their responses, jot them quickly on the board.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage students to use their own words; they don't need to say \"Confidentiality\" if what they mean is \"don’t let strangers read your stuff.\" The point is to reinforce the core ideas, not the jargon."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f880acef-8db3-4c3f-9ff3-a47f373502e3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c889e6f8-ef12-404c-aa42-7b3db66d414f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1c4ebbce-2488-4b33-a551-5803495bb72a",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1c4ebbce-2488-4b33-a551-5803495bb72a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c889e6f8-ef12-404c-aa42-7b3db66d414f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "aad376ef-c645-4421-9cde-49b61496302d",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Key Vocabulary."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "aad376ef-c645-4421-9cde-49b61496302d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c889e6f8-ef12-404c-aa42-7b3db66d414f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "67e6d2fb-88e4-4f5e-9685-d2a0344a8b5e",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Student Survey"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "67e6d2fb-88e4-4f5e-9685-d2a0344a8b5e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c889e6f8-ef12-404c-aa42-7b3db66d414f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "89798f4b-11f6-4d1a-a417-68b2b424722c",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How would you prove you are YOU if you can't show your face?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should identify common ways to prove identity, like something you know (a password), have (a phone), or are (a fingerprint). Listen for examples in each category and prompt students to distinguish identity from access. If a student says \"my voice\" or \"my face\" follow up with: \"AI can deepfake that now…so now what?\" The key takeaway is that authentication methods can be fooled, especially by AI, which makes understanding them even more important.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage students to build on others' ideas and remind them that it's okay to pass if they need more time to think."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "89798f4b-11f6-4d1a-a417-68b2b424722c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e782a540-634d-4292-8893-28c19e73c2ab"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "87e54cf5-cc80-44de-84b2-6ddb5acefda2",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "87e54cf5-cc80-44de-84b2-6ddb5acefda2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e782a540-634d-4292-8893-28c19e73c2ab"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "12aaed9d-5f6a-46de-be07-891d2197897c",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "12aaed9d-5f6a-46de-be07-891d2197897c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e782a540-634d-4292-8893-28c19e73c2ab"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a4253089-7649-4dec-9fe9-c4b27df38704",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullseye-arrow\"></i> Goal of this activity: Introduce the three terms: Authentication, Access Control, Accounting and ensure students understand the differences and nuances between the different tools.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "AAA Vocab"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a4253089-7649-4dec-9fe9-c4b27df38704",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4b739aac-b478-4e0a-88c8-642b9860b09a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7111376c-dee6-4660-9b2e-d1af8943c43c",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Today we're diving into three important tools that help protect the CIA Triad. These are the foundation of how companies and apps decide who you are and what you’re allowed to do.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7111376c-dee6-4660-9b2e-d1af8943c43c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4b739aac-b478-4e0a-88c8-642b9860b09a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e7780448-26ad-4952-8954-d52d07586737",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students take out their AI Powered Threat and Defenses Unit Guide and turn to the section for this lesson."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e7780448-26ad-4952-8954-d52d07586737",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4b739aac-b478-4e0a-88c8-642b9860b09a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "30d8b0a6-ac6a-488d-909f-2dfa83bd39b4",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "AAA stands for Authentication, Access Control, and Accounting. These are the tools systems use to figure out who you are, what you're allowed to do, and what you actually did. Whether you're logging into a game, checking your grades, or using a shared playlist, AAA tools help manage and protect that experience. Today's activities are going to dive into Authentication and Access Control. We will get a deeper look into Accounting in the next lesson.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "30d8b0a6-ac6a-488d-909f-2dfa83bd39b4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4b739aac-b478-4e0a-88c8-642b9860b09a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6df08634-9b55-4892-b53c-7b216f288ab1",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *AAA Tools*. Explain that these are three core tools used in cybersecurity to protect data and manage user access.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Write \"Authentication\", \"Access Control\", and \"Accounting\" on the board as visible anchors for the rest of the lesson."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6df08634-9b55-4892-b53c-7b216f288ab1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4b739aac-b478-4e0a-88c8-642b9860b09a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2d75f4e4-f872-4cf0-9325-86f77332103f",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2d75f4e4-f872-4cf0-9325-86f77332103f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4b739aac-b478-4e0a-88c8-642b9860b09a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c24d35ea-61e6-446e-a775-6cf26c8f62f8",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *Authentication*.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "As you explain, point out each category — 'know', 'have', 'are' — and connect to everyday tools: passwords, phones, and biometrics like fingerprints or Face ID."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c24d35ea-61e6-446e-a775-6cf26c8f62f8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4b739aac-b478-4e0a-88c8-642b9860b09a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "bc0e8b95-a3cf-4ec8-aa04-8eccdf1c616b",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "bc0e8b95-a3cf-4ec8-aa04-8eccdf1c616b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4b739aac-b478-4e0a-88c8-642b9860b09a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "47d406e4-21a5-4f5b-a8c7-8f5d09f7d62f",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *Access Control*. Clarify that access control only matters once a system knows who you are; it's the next step after authentication.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain the three most common access control types listed for students in their Unit Guide (RBAC, DAC, ABAC). Provide additional examples if needed.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use examples students will recognize, like how students can view their grades, but only teachers can change them. These real-world connections make access control more tangible."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "47d406e4-21a5-4f5b-a8c7-8f5d09f7d62f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4b739aac-b478-4e0a-88c8-642b9860b09a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c2828b33-1a60-4edc-9d47-92e961ce7264",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c2828b33-1a60-4edc-9d47-92e961ce7264",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4b739aac-b478-4e0a-88c8-642b9860b09a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "64650998-d8f1-4f92-a43c-52546309c3b2",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Think back to last class when you were dealing with the different scenarios. Some of the issues that you identified are things that will connect with what you will be doing at today’s stations.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "64650998-d8f1-4f92-a43c-52546309c3b2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4b739aac-b478-4e0a-88c8-642b9860b09a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "468baffb-e774-47cd-9a93-a1c99e875cab",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullseye-arrow\"></i> **Goal of this activity:** Students apply their understanding of access control types by choosing a real-world scenario, designing a rule for managing access, and connecting it to something they’ve experienced in their own lives\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain what students will do at Station A: sort authentication cards into three categories: What You Know, What You Have, and What You Are, identify one method per category that could be vulnerable to AI and explain how, and brainstorm one new example per category and add it to the class poster.",
        "duration": "25",
        "name": "AAA Stations",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Make sure students know to compare how they sorted the cards with the answer sheet on the Station A poster. Let students know that if they get anything incorrect on the card sort, they should mix up the cards and try again."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "468baffb-e774-47cd-9a93-a1c99e875cab",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4b739aac-b478-4e0a-88c8-642b9860b09a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "67e0851c-51d9-4dc3-ba41-dd7640e88d21",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "67e0851c-51d9-4dc3-ba41-dd7640e88d21",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4b739aac-b478-4e0a-88c8-642b9860b09a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a2424da2-5ac6-45c6-8ca5-c63ec4f74848",
      "position": 14,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain what students will do at Station B: choose a scenario card and write an access rule using the sentence frame: \"If [conditions], then [grant/deny] access,\" label the rule with one of the three access models (RBAC, DAC, or ABAC), add a short explanation of why that model fits, post the card on the appropriate column of the Station B poster, and add a sticky note describing a real-life example they've seen.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Let students know that if they are finished with one scenario card before it is time to rotate, that they should pick a second scenario card from the pile."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a2424da2-5ac6-45c6-8ca5-c63ec4f74848",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4b739aac-b478-4e0a-88c8-642b9860b09a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b4536055-d54f-4c42-a437-0422ee50dece",
      "position": 15,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b4536055-d54f-4c42-a437-0422ee50dece",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4b739aac-b478-4e0a-88c8-642b9860b09a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "221209b4-85aa-467c-8b78-88eed6df0f8b",
      "position": 16,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Display the station reminders as students work at the stations. Emphasize that students will visit both stations in any order.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Look for students mislabeling cards or struggling to explain why a method fits a category (at Station A), or mixing up the access control models (at Station B). Listen for vague sticky notes and encourage students to be specific. Offer prompts like:\n- \"Can AI really trick that, or is it harder than it seems?\"\n- \"What makes this access rule discretionary vs role-based?\"\n- \"How does your example connect to your rule?\"\n\nEncourage stronger examples or clearer access conditions when students seem unsure.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Keep a timer visible or use a chime/bell to keep transitions smooth.\n\nTo support different learners, at the Access Control station, students who finish early can pick a second scenario card or compare two access control models for the same situation. If students need support, offer example cards or model thinking aloud by asking, \"Which part of the situation matters most for deciding access?\"\n\nAt the Authentication station, students who finish early can try creating a second new example per category, or explain which method they think is most secure and why. For students who need support, guide them in thinking about how AI could mimic something you know, have, or are."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "221209b4-85aa-467c-8b78-88eed6df0f8b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4b739aac-b478-4e0a-88c8-642b9860b09a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "85f7c46f-35e7-4e4c-81a1-48a86587430e",
      "position": 17,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "85f7c46f-35e7-4e4c-81a1-48a86587430e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4b739aac-b478-4e0a-88c8-642b9860b09a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8280cb69-ac0e-4b32-8a7d-4c3635de981f",
      "position": 18,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students reset their stations in anticipation of switching by following the directions listed here.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Make sure that students have reset their stations properly and have shared their work (sticky notes & cards) in the appropriate place.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Close the station work with a quick \"Top Takeaways\" or \"Mic Drop Moment\". Invite 2–3 students to share a sticky, scenario, or aha moment they found interesting at the stations. This reinforces learning and helps surface strong examples before the QOTD reflection.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 7, Level 1 to complete the formative assessment.",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "Use these two questions to formatively assess both lesson objectives: understanding how systems verify identity (authentication) and manage access (access control). Look for common misconceptions, such as:\n- Confusing authentication with access control\n- Missing or vague explanations (e.g., “logging in” without saying how or why)\n- Not connecting access control to user roles or models like RBAC\n\nIf needed, pause for a quick class discussion, model a strong sample answer, or invite peer feedback before moving on."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8280cb69-ac0e-4b32-8a7d-4c3635de981f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4b739aac-b478-4e0a-88c8-642b9860b09a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "81e62a9d-e8c5-4514-be29-139fdcf643b3",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullseye-arrow\"></i> **Goal of this activity:** Summarize what authentication and access control mean and how they help protect digital systems.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to turn to the Question of the Day in their Unit Guide. Have them discuss both prompts in their Unit Guide with a partner, then write down their individual responses. Let them know they’ll be sharing these ideas with classmates in the next activity.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use Unit Guide responses and partner discussions to check for understanding. Listen for common misconceptions, such as:\n- Confusing authentication with access control\n- Vague responses (e.g., “Authentication is logging in”)\n- Incorrectly matching examples to AAA terms\n\nIf needed:\n- Ask students to explain their answers in their own words\n- Pair students to revise and clarify thinking\n- Reread the AAA definitions as a class or do a quick thumbs-up/thumbs-down check"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "81e62a9d-e8c5-4514-be29-139fdcf643b3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "8ececb35-8213-4931-8d19-73f2243d998b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3875ad25-c513-4b1d-9249-660139e4ffb3",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3875ad25-c513-4b1d-9249-660139e4ffb3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "8ececb35-8213-4931-8d19-73f2243d998b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a06e8406-3b69-4fd1-a881-0822ed114a0e",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Key Vocabulary.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 7, Level 1 to complete the End of Lesson Survey.",
        "progression_name": "Student Survey"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a06e8406-3b69-4fd1-a881-0822ed114a0e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "8ececb35-8213-4931-8d19-73f2243d998b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5144a0b5-3daa-48be-af9b-e38f13060143",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullseye-arrow\"></i> **Goal of this activity:** Activate student understanding of what \"anomaly\" means and how humans detect them."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5144a0b5-3daa-48be-af9b-e38f13060143",
        "lesson_activity.key": "09fa8e1b-81ee-4f3f-811e-3e7c58abc92a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2478aa75-09ea-4813-bba8-77edbb82dd83",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Look at the data shown here. Most data points follow a pattern, but one clearly stands out as unusual or unexpected. We call that an anomaly.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2478aa75-09ea-4813-bba8-77edbb82dd83",
        "lesson_activity.key": "09fa8e1b-81ee-4f3f-811e-3e7c58abc92a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "97dcda9d-1a4e-4e4f-ac03-815835656927",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students' attention to the highlighted data point.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n- *How do we (as humans) decide something is an anomaly?*\n- *What types of behavior make us suspicious?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Encourage students to reflect on how humans decide something is an anomaly or suspicious. Invite them to share specific examples—like noticing strange purchases on a credit card, unusual login activity, or odd behavior in a friend—and to consider patterns like late-night activity, unexpected locations, or sudden changes in communication. Help students recognize that what seems suspicious can vary depending on personal experience, cultural background, or individual bias.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "97dcda9d-1a4e-4e4f-ac03-815835656927",
        "lesson_activity.key": "09fa8e1b-81ee-4f3f-811e-3e7c58abc92a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a9c1a809-d739-4667-aaa2-d74196ff25c0",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullseye-arrow\"></i> **Goal of this activity:** Analyze and detect anomalies in user data and compare human findings to AI outputs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students take out their AI Powered Threat and Defenses Unit Guide and turn to the section for this lesson.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Remind students what they learned about Authentication and Access Control in the last lesson. Emphasize that both of those tools only work when the system can keep a record of user activity—which is what Accounting (also called Auditing) is for.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define Accounting. Let students know that this \"A\" of the AAA framework is sometimes called \"Auditing,\" and that in many contexts, Accounting and Auditing mean the same thing: tracking what users do. Viewing the Version History of a document is a form of accounting because it helps track who accessed what and when.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Fraud Detection Investigation"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a9c1a809-d739-4667-aaa2-d74196ff25c0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "22c43c40-a6af-4d1c-971d-bb97101dc412"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "25b940be-b1b0-4eb4-8e3f-0b2e5e721864",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Today, you are going to review different logs that were gathered as part of the Accounting step of the AAA framework. With your partner, you will be examining these logs and looking for anomalies that seem suspicious.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "25b940be-b1b0-4eb4-8e3f-0b2e5e721864",
        "lesson_activity.key": "22c43c40-a6af-4d1c-971d-bb97101dc412"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b7c56253-2881-49d2-8120-1886b2ff5808",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Put students into groups of two.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each group of students a copy of the Fraud Detection Investigation activity guide and one of the User Persona Audit Logs.",
        "progression_name": "Fraud Detection Investigation",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "The Fraud Detection activity guide and User Persona Audit Logs are also provided in Lesson 8, Level 1 for classes that would prefer to view them online."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b7c56253-2881-49d2-8120-1886b2ff5808",
        "lesson_activity.key": "22c43c40-a6af-4d1c-971d-bb97101dc412"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9d86aa19-bcaa-4fcb-bc73-e6f64d944339",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9d86aa19-bcaa-4fcb-bc73-e6f64d944339",
        "lesson_activity.key": "22c43c40-a6af-4d1c-971d-bb97101dc412"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5721527f-b5af-4f6f-9c5b-e1b5e18edea2",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to examine the audit logs for their user and look for suspicious activity or anomalies. Remind them to use the user profile as context—what's suspicious for this person—and to record their reasoning in the activity guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Prompt students to refer back to the User Profile. Ask: \"Would this activity be suspicious for your user?\" Encourage students to explain their thinking, not just flag unusual entries.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Watch for students who flag something just because it looks strange (\"Toronto at 3 AM\") without checking if it actually conflicts with the user profile. If students finish early, ask them to compare with a group that has a different user: \"Would this be suspicious for your user too?\" This keeps early finishers engaged and pushes deeper reasoning."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5721527f-b5af-4f6f-9c5b-e1b5e18edea2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "22c43c40-a6af-4d1c-971d-bb97101dc412"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ec886f68-afd9-44d2-b341-8d1b7c4dadbe",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ec886f68-afd9-44d2-b341-8d1b7c4dadbe",
        "lesson_activity.key": "22c43c40-a6af-4d1c-971d-bb97101dc412"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d7b75e09-0d8f-49a0-ae8b-12112ee86fad",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How might AI assist with fraud detection?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** The goal here is to guide students to identify specific advantages of AI, such as quickly scanning large datasets, recognizing subtle or repetitive patterns, or catching events humans might miss due to oversight or fatigue. Prompt students to consider real-world examples, such as how banks or online platforms use AI to identify suspicious transactions or logins."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d7b75e09-0d8f-49a0-ae8b-12112ee86fad",
        "lesson_activity.key": "22c43c40-a6af-4d1c-971d-bb97101dc412"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "314ef846-1692-4edc-bba9-add400840166",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "You just thought about how AI might help with fraud detection—now let's see what it actually does. Let's compare your findings to the AI's analysis.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "AI Model Training",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "314ef846-1692-4edc-bba9-add400840166",
        "lesson_activity.key": "22c43c40-a6af-4d1c-971d-bb97101dc412"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "bbc6afac-b7ec-49d1-85ab-39cfe8a8ca63",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 8, Level 2 to attach their user's logs that they analyzed and ask the AI to flag suspicious activity. Students should then compare their analysis to the AI's, checking if the AI flagged the same suspicious events, looking for anomalies the AI might have missed, and noting if the AI found something humans overlooked.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** As students work, make sure they record what the AI flagged and answer the reflection questions in Part 1 of their activity guide. Ask students:\n- Why do you think the AI flagged that one?\n- Would that seem suspicious for your user?\n- Why might the AI miss something a person noticed—or vice versa?",
        "progression_name": "Human vs AI Detection"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "bbc6afac-b7ec-49d1-85ab-39cfe8a8ca63",
        "lesson_activity.key": "22c43c40-a6af-4d1c-971d-bb97101dc412"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7c4399a0-9e1a-411b-8f3a-f2c1a48aa92a",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Part 2 of their activity guide. In this section, they read four login scenarios based on their user persona and predict the A'’s risk score and required authentication method for each one. They record their predictions and reasoning, focusing on what an AI system might flag based on patterns—not just what seems risky to them personally.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** As you move around the room, check that students are using the user profile context to inform their predictions.  Prompt deeper reasoning by asking:\n- Why do you think the AI would treat this as high risk?\n- What part of this behavior feels normal for your user?\n- What combination of factors are you noticing?",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Some students may struggle with middle-ground cases. Encourage them to justify their predictions, even if they aren't sure.\n If time allows, invite early finishers to compare predictions with another group who had a different persona and ask: \"Would your AI react the same way to this scenario?\""
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7c4399a0-9e1a-411b-8f3a-f2c1a48aa92a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "22c43c40-a6af-4d1c-971d-bb97101dc412"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ff424e22-b8f7-4940-8185-afc8f7c1db9e",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ff424e22-b8f7-4940-8185-afc8f7c1db9e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "22c43c40-a6af-4d1c-971d-bb97101dc412"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e5732a21-e8dd-4d92-8f07-f1767a037c68",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 8, Level 3 and 4.\n- Level 3: Students attach their user’s scenarios and compare their predictions and authentication methods to the AI’s results.\n- Level 4: Students complete a check for understanding\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** As students compare their predictions to the AI's decisions, ask: \"Why do you think the AI flagged this as high risk?\" and \"What factors do you think mattered most in the AI's decision?\" These questions support the goal of helping students understand how AI systems make real-time, pattern-based security decisions.",
        "progression_name": "Adaptive Security",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Student responses on Level 4 can be used to formatively assess their understanding of the lesson objectives. This question checks whether students can recognize the kinds of behavioral patterns AI uses to assign risk and adjust authentication requirements.\nIf students answer incorrectly:\n- Revisit one of the risk scenarios from earlier and walk through how each factor contributes to the score.\n- Reinforce that AI systems often rely on combinations of unusual factors (new device + odd time + unfamiliar location), not isolated behaviors.\n- Consider asking students to create an alternative high-risk scenario as a quick extension.\n\nIf most students get it right:\n- Use it as a launchpad to ask: \"Could there be someone for whom that pattern isn't suspicious? What might the AI miss?\""
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e5732a21-e8dd-4d92-8f07-f1767a037c68",
        "lesson_activity.key": "22c43c40-a6af-4d1c-971d-bb97101dc412"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "963dc3dc-0412-4d8b-b02d-d9c66fe5806c",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "963dc3dc-0412-4d8b-b02d-d9c66fe5806c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "22c43c40-a6af-4d1c-971d-bb97101dc412"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "648e9b46-ccad-4fbb-9e5f-41585fc67763",
      "position": 14,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click the animated slide to display the prompts.\n- *How does an AI model learn to recognize patterns?*\n- *Where do those patterns come from?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** The goal is to help students to recall that AI doesn't \"think\" or \"guess\"—it learns by finding patterns in labeled examples. The goal is to reinforce that AI models are trained using many examples tagged with what they mean (e.g., \"suspicious\" vs. \"normal\"), and the AI uses repetition to recognize what those categories look like. This primes students to write their own \"if-then\" rules by thinking like a machine learning model, not a person."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "648e9b46-ccad-4fbb-9e5f-41585fc67763",
        "lesson_activity.key": "22c43c40-a6af-4d1c-971d-bb97101dc412"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "91b0ca76-f050-407f-a3c3-99beec5bcc93",
      "position": 15,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to look for any patterns in their user's four scenarios and create a general \"fraud rule\" in their activity guide that an AI could be trained to follow. This can be a simple if-then statement the AI could follow if it were trained on the user persona and data artifacts that the students examined in Part One\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** As students write their fraud rules, check whether their patterns include more than one factor (e.g., time + location + device). Ask students: \"What behavior is the AI supposed to watch for?\" and  \"Would this rule work for anyone, or is it specific to your user?\" Encourage students to revise their rule if it's too general or only tied to one isolated event.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Adaptive Access Controls",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If students are stuck, invite them to revisit one of their four scenarios and ask, \"What would I want the AI to do if this happened again?\" That can help them build a fraud rule based on a specific example instead of abstracting from scratch."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "91b0ca76-f050-407f-a3c3-99beec5bcc93",
        "lesson_activity.key": "22c43c40-a6af-4d1c-971d-bb97101dc412"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a1010524-3947-4b18-b4b7-4fe8194f81d4",
      "position": 16,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a1010524-3947-4b18-b4b7-4fe8194f81d4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "22c43c40-a6af-4d1c-971d-bb97101dc412"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9392d738-0d9a-445b-85cc-3d848447d557",
      "position": 17,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Invite a few students to share their fraud rules and how their user's background or behavior influenced their decisions. Highlight that different users lead to different ideas of what' \"normal\" or \"suspicious.\" Emphasize that AI trained on limited data may misjudge people from different communities, lifestyles, or tech habits.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click the animated slide to display the prompts.\n- *What patterns did the AI seem to follow when assigning risk?*\n- *How were those patterns similar to or different from the fraud rule you wrote?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** The goal is to help students synthesize what they've learned about how AI detects threats by recognizing patterns in behavior, and how that leads to adaptive authentication decisions. This discussion also gives students a chance to reflect on the relationship between the fraud rule they created and the kinds of reasoning AI systems use. The goal is to deepen understanding of how AI supports security features like fraud detection, anomaly detection, and adaptive access control.\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "Student responses can be used to formatively assess understanding of the lesson objectives, particularly whether students can:\n- Accurately describe how AI identifies suspicious patterns in data\n- Analyze how AI's pattern detection influences security actions like authentication requirements\n\nIf student responses show confusion about:\n- How the AI calculated risk, revisit a sample scenario and model the AI's logic aloud.\n- How AI connects to security features, refer back to the \"AI in AAA\" slide or the Risk Calculator demo and reframe the model as an automated decision-maker, not a human reasoner.\n- How their fraud rule connects to AI training, ask students to underline what part of their rule the AI seemed to follow or ignore.\n\nIf most students respond with vague or surface-level ideas, consider:\n- Having them return to one of their risk scenarios and revise their fraud rule\n- Asking partners to swap and critique each other's rules using the AI's logic as a benchmark"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9392d738-0d9a-445b-85cc-3d848447d557",
        "lesson_activity.key": "22c43c40-a6af-4d1c-971d-bb97101dc412"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c7404189-32f7-4d26-8ba1-95933e48f9b1",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to turn to the Question of the Day in their Unit Guide. Invite each student to share their \"mic drop\" insight. This should be a concise, bold statement about AI and digital security they now believe to be true. Frame it as \"One thing I’ll remember about AI in cybersecurity is...\"",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Consider playing upbeat music quietly in the background as students take turns delivering their lines around the room. It might also be interesting to create a class \"Mic Drop Wall\" on chart paper where students write their closing thought for others to read."
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "Use the Unit Guide responses and partner conversations to gauge students’ understanding of the lesson objectives. As students write and discuss their answers, listen for common misconceptions:\n- Students who confuse authentication with access control (e.g., thinking passwords control what you're allowed to do).\n- Vague or overly general answers (e.g., \"Authentication is logging in\" without explanation).\n- Incorrect matching of examples to the AAA terms.\n\nIf you notice confusion:\n- Prompt students to explain their answers out loud and clarify in their own words.\n- Pair students with stronger responses with those who need support, and have them talk through their thinking before revising their answers.\n- Consider rereading the AAA definitions as a class or doing a quick thumbs-up/thumbs-down check on example scenarios.\n- Ask the class: “Which part of this was easiest to explain? Which was hardest?” and use that to spark a mini reteach or group discussion before moving to “Give One, Get One.”"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c7404189-32f7-4d26-8ba1-95933e48f9b1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3f080b8e-ad7b-4f45-a386-831f8055d94f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "12517cfe-bee6-4a43-954a-95b2a874d315",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "12517cfe-bee6-4a43-954a-95b2a874d315",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3f080b8e-ad7b-4f45-a386-831f8055d94f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "184263a1-1e13-4f2e-ac41-5d08dab38697",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Key Vocabulary.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 8, Level 6 to complete the End of Lesson Survey.",
        "progression_name": "Student Survey"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "184263a1-1e13-4f2e-ac41-5d08dab38697",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3f080b8e-ad7b-4f45-a386-831f8055d94f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "036b7b5f-e079-44e9-8845-baa7f1c7d999",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullseye-arrow\"></i> **Goal of this activity:** Introduce encryption through a short, scaffolded Caesar cipher activity that includes productive struggle and active use of a key. Set students up to think critically about how encryption systems are designed.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Display the encrypted message."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "036b7b5f-e079-44e9-8845-baa7f1c7d999",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f21ec793-4c0f-4d65-b8fa-242d2dec30a8"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "db269c60-96a2-4263-8e2e-811a095e0e41",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "This is a secret message. You don’t know the method or the key . . . yet. See if you can figure out how to decode it.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "db269c60-96a2-4263-8e2e-811a095e0e41",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f21ec793-4c0f-4d65-b8fa-242d2dec30a8"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "29487cf3-c078-4a99-acc9-9d240d7b1a62",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Wait 1–2 minutes for students to try decoding the message on their own. Don’t give them any clues at first — encourage productive struggle. After a minute or when a student asks, let them know this is a Caesar cipher — a type of encryption that shifts each letter by a fixed amount.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Some students may immediately ask “What are we supposed to do?” or freeze if they don’t get it. Reassure them that it’s okay to guess or play with the pattern. Try prompting students with: “What do you notice about the letters?” or “Try shifting a few letters and see what happens.”\nConsider encouraging students to jot down the alphabet on scratch paper. This helps them visualize letter shifts and supports pattern-based learners."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "29487cf3-c078-4a99-acc9-9d240d7b1a62",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f21ec793-4c0f-4d65-b8fa-242d2dec30a8"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d5c21077-e149-41f6-a746-d800fd8a80cf",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-video-camera\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Video:** Show the \"Encryption & Public Key\" video from 00:55 - 1:45 to introduce Caesar Cipher.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Before playing the clip, read the two questions aloud and tell students to watch for the answers:\n- How does the Caesar Cipher method work?\n- What is a key?\n\nAfter the video, ask for a few quick responses before moving to the next slide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should recognize that the Caesar Cipher is a substitution method that shifts letters in the alphabet using a numerical value called a key. The key is what allows someone to both encrypt and decrypt a message, and without it, the message appears meaningless. This sets up the foundational idea that encryption relies on a repeatable rule + a shared secret.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that a Caesar cipher works by shifting each letter in the alphabet a certain number of places. That number, the amount you shift, is called the key. You can shift forward or backward, but both people need to know the key to decode the message.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If students are still unclear, try a quick example on the board: \"Let's say we shift every letter forward by 2 — A becomes C, B becomes D, and so on.\" Visual learners benefit from seeing the letter mapping laid out, especially if you circle back to this later during the design challenge."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d5c21077-e149-41f6-a746-d800fd8a80cf",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f21ec793-4c0f-4d65-b8fa-242d2dec30a8"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "970b1f66-1b30-4273-816e-868884537f91",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "970b1f66-1b30-4273-816e-868884537f91",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f21ec793-4c0f-4d65-b8fa-242d2dec30a8"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "11535c93-8d8c-434b-878d-e369d038a88e",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Display the encrypted message again, this time along with the method (“shift letters backward”) and the key (“shift by 3”).  Give students another 1–2 minutes to try decoding it.  Then click to reveal the decrypted message: “This message is secret.”",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "- Write the alphabet on the board and show how to use the key to shift a letter — for example, shift “W” back 3 letters to get “T.”\n- Encourage students to do the same on a scrap piece of paper. Seeing the full alphabet helps them visualize the shifts and makes both encoding and decoding easier.\n- There is a Caesar Cipher wheel provided as an optional resource if you would like your students to use that manipulative.\n\nOptional Mini-Extension (If Time Allows or for Fast Finishers):  Ask students to create their own short message and encrypt it using a Caesar cipher with a different shift (like +4 or +7). Then, swap messages with a partner and try to decode each other's message using the new key."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "11535c93-8d8c-434b-878d-e369d038a88e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f21ec793-4c0f-4d65-b8fa-242d2dec30a8"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1dfa38b7-c3fa-4ce8-9c10-625721a3655c",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1dfa38b7-c3fa-4ce8-9c10-625721a3655c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f21ec793-4c0f-4d65-b8fa-242d2dec30a8"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2346447f-361c-43da-8a1b-055c8aab9da0",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n- *What made the secret message hard to decrypt at first?*\n- *What changed once you knew the method and the key?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** This discussion aims to help students understand that encryption works because of a repeatable method and a secret key. Without them, the message looks like nonsense — but with them, it becomes readable. This sets up key ideas they’ll explore later, like the importance of keeping keys secret, and balancing strength with usability."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2346447f-361c-43da-8a1b-055c8aab9da0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f21ec793-4c0f-4d65-b8fa-242d2dec30a8"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3c093c50-4a73-4002-a833-f1222970fa4d",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "The Caesar cipher is one of the oldest known encryption methods, and you just used it. But could you invent something stronger? Faster? Stranger? That's your next challenge!",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3c093c50-4a73-4002-a833-f1222970fa4d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f21ec793-4c0f-4d65-b8fa-242d2dec30a8"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "53a3a3ab-f22c-4e6a-b6d8-0802aa90567f",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "53a3a3ab-f22c-4e6a-b6d8-0802aa90567f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f21ec793-4c0f-4d65-b8fa-242d2dec30a8"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f140fc4d-5fac-4a86-bb69-e9b1f5ab5c59",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullseye-arrow\"></i> **Goal of this activity:**  Help students define foundational encryption terms (encryption and decryption), then apply those concepts by designing their own encryption method. This creative challenge encourages students to balance security and usability and prepares them to compare their system to real-world encryption types later in the lesson.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students take out their AI Powered Threat and Defenses Unit Guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define encryption. Provide students an example such as: Encryption is what scrambles your data when you send a text or store a password. Without the right key, someone else can't read it.",
        "duration": "20",
        "name": "Encryption Design Challenge",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Students may associate encryption with passwords or messaging apps but not know exactly what it means. You can reinforce that encryption doesn't just hide data — it makes it unreadable unless you have a way to unlock it. This sets up the need for a key in the next slide."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f140fc4d-5fac-4a86-bb69-e9b1f5ab5c59",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e7dcbf63-907d-4545-8ff4-fba8c6c5c122"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "db11563c-590d-4456-9f60-e074fdaa6e84",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "db11563c-590d-4456-9f60-e074fdaa6e84",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e7dcbf63-907d-4545-8ff4-fba8c6c5c122"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "107799a1-7647-4790-924b-2c9f014d5396",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *decryption*. Tell students that decryption is what happens when someone uses the correct key to unlock a scrambled message. It's the reverse of encryption — turning unreadable data back into something that makes sense.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Students may think of \"decryption\" as something only hackers do. Let them know that every time they unlock a phone, read a secure message, or use a password manager, decryption is happening in the background — using a key their device already knows."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "107799a1-7647-4790-924b-2c9f014d5396",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e7dcbf63-907d-4545-8ff4-fba8c6c5c122"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "41a28ded-d266-40ee-aefe-c994393fa3ab",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "41a28ded-d266-40ee-aefe-c994393fa3ab",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e7dcbf63-907d-4545-8ff4-fba8c6c5c122"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a1aa9d62-5d26-4a12-950e-d473debd48d4",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Place students into groups of two or three.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each pair of students a copy of the Encryption Design Challenge activity guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to work with their group to invent their own encryption method that scrambles a message and can be decrypted only by someone with the right key, rule, or pattern.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** As groups work, ask open-ended questions to deepen thinking:\n- What makes your encryption secure?\n- Could someone decode it without knowing the key?\n- Would a computer or person be better at cracking this?\n- What tradeoff are you making between security and ease of use?",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Struggling students:\n- If students feel stuck, reassure them that their method doesn't need to be super complex — it just needs to scramble a message and include a way to decode it.\n- If they need a creative boost, have them draw an Encryption Inspiration Card to get started. They can adapt or build on the idea to create a method that works for them.\n\nEarly Finishers:\n- Encourage students who finish early to try to increase the complexity of their design by adding more layers to their method.\n- Early finishers should also test their method on a short sentence and write both the encrypted and decrypted versions."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a1aa9d62-5d26-4a12-950e-d473debd48d4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e7dcbf63-907d-4545-8ff4-fba8c6c5c122"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3752ad42-b82e-4487-8e8f-b1e1568e4337",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3752ad42-b82e-4487-8e8f-b1e1568e4337",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e7dcbf63-907d-4545-8ff4-fba8c6c5c122"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "65c4a6e0-53ea-4d32-a24d-31f30aa91d0c",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What made an encryption method seem strong? Is strong always better?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** This discussion helps students reflect on what made encryption systems \"strong\" in their design challenge — and whether those strengths came with tradeoffs. Encourage students to consider how usable or understandable their methods were, and whether a message that’s too hard to decode is still useful. This discussion sets the stage for comparing real-world encryption methods later in the lesson.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If students are curious about how real encryption is used, you can introduce examples like AES and RSA.\nExplain that AES is often used to protect stored data because it's fast and efficient, while RSA is used to securely share keys between systems.\nThese are real-world examples of the symmetric and asymmetric encryption types students will learn more about later in the lesson.\nUse this preview to show how encryption design decisions happen in actual systems — where security, speed, and usability must be balanced."
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "As students reflect on what makes encryption \"strong\", listen for how well they:\n- Identify the features that made a system feel secure (e.g., complexity, hidden patterns, unpredictability)\n- Consider whether the method was too difficult or impractical to use\n- Recognize the tradeoff between strength and usability\n- Compare how their method worked versus others' in terms of clarity, difficulty, or purpose\n\nOn Track if students say:\n- “It was hard to break, but we had trouble remembering how to use it.”\n- “It worked, but if someone didn’t know the rule exactly, they couldn’t decode it.”\n- “Ours was simple and fast, but maybe not very secure.”\n- “I think it’s better for fun messages than for real data.”\n\nThese responses show students are beginning to reason like system designers — balancing security, clarity, and real-world use.\nIf you hear these, move forward confidently. Consider highlighting a few aloud: “That’s the kind of tradeoff real engineers face — how to keep things secure and usable.”\n\nIf Students Struggle:\nIf you hear:\n- \"Stronger is always better.\"\n- “You just make it random and confusing.”\n- “The more complicated it is, the safer it is — no matter what.”\n\nTry this:\n- Prompt with a follow-up: “Would this work if you needed to send a quick message to a friend?”\n- Ask: “If even you can’t explain how to decode it, is it practical?”\n- Reframe: “Imagine you're the person receiving this message — what would you need to know to read it?”"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "65c4a6e0-53ea-4d32-a24d-31f30aa91d0c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e7dcbf63-907d-4545-8ff4-fba8c6c5c122"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4343d06d-dd88-4e6d-83e3-4ed9d2703dbd",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4343d06d-dd88-4e6d-83e3-4ed9d2703dbd",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e7dcbf63-907d-4545-8ff4-fba8c6c5c122"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b3290307-7fa9-4a89-b7c8-cc5168d44b07",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullseye-arrow\"></i> **Goal of this activity:** Help students understand symmetric encryption and connect it to their earlier design work. This sets the foundation for analyzing how encryption methods are used in different data states.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define symmetric encryption. Ensure students understand that in symmetric encryption, both people need to have the same secret key. That key is used to scramble the message and also to unlock it. It’s fast and efficient — but it only works if the key stays secret and both people have it.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Encryption Types and Data States",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "This section introduces several key concepts and requires students to reflect on how their encryption method connects to real-world systems. Students will define new terms, watch a short video, apply what they learn to a data states table, and answer two reflection questions. Be mindful of pacing — consider setting time limits for each step or prioritizing what to revisit in a class discussion later if needed."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b3290307-7fa9-4a89-b7c8-cc5168d44b07",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e7dcbf63-907d-4545-8ff4-fba8c6c5c122"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "79f4e51e-8faf-4121-8d0c-93b52ddeeaeb",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "79f4e51e-8faf-4121-8d0c-93b52ddeeaeb",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e7dcbf63-907d-4545-8ff4-fba8c6c5c122"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "43a61e2e-fc97-497e-972d-52cd8a21536f",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *asymmetric encryption*. Ensure students understand that asymmetric encryption uses two keys. Anyone can use your public key to lock a message — but only you can unlock it using your private key. That’s how secure messages can be exchanged between people who haven’t met before.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Students may be confused by the idea of two different keys. Let them know they'll watch a short video next that uses a real-world analogy to make this concept easier to understand. Encourage them to look for: Which key is shared, which one stays private, and why would this be useful."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "43a61e2e-fc97-497e-972d-52cd8a21536f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e7dcbf63-907d-4545-8ff4-fba8c6c5c122"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "cf882d5d-8594-4ba5-8c2a-3e4bc84a1513",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "cf882d5d-8594-4ba5-8c2a-3e4bc84a1513",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e7dcbf63-907d-4545-8ff4-fba8c6c5c122"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "159d6207-ef0a-4e5e-b1a8-a1ea9ff661a0",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-video-camera\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Video:** Show the \"Encryption & Public Key\" video from 4:10 - 5:40 to explain symmetric and asymmetric encryption.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Before playing the clip, read the question aloud and tell students to watch for the answers:\n- What is the difference between symmetric and asymmetric encryption?\n- Based on what you see, which type best matches the encryption method you designed?\n\nAfter the video, ask students to turn and talk or briefly share out which method they think they created — and why.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should be able to explain the basic difference between symmetric (same key for locking and unlocking) and asymmetric (two different keys: one public, one private). More importantly, they should begin to analyze their own encryption design and identify whether it aligns more closely with one method or the other — and why. This prepares them to reflect more deeply in the Code Studio questions that follow.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "The video explains the concept of asymmetric encryption using a mailbox metaphor. If students seem confused after watching, try revisiting the key distinction:\n- Symmetric = same key to lock and unlock\n- Asymmetric = two different keys: one to lock (public), one to unlock (private)\n\nAsk: “Why might asymmetric encryption be more useful when the two people don’t know each other yet?”"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "159d6207-ef0a-4e5e-b1a8-a1ea9ff661a0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e7dcbf63-907d-4545-8ff4-fba8c6c5c122"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f339ca3c-3f58-4890-bba8-b1229ca98c31",
      "position": 14,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We just talked about how encryption keeps data safe, but data doesn't just sit in one place. It moves and changes, like a message on your phone that's stored, sent, and read. We protect data at different times.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f339ca3c-3f58-4890-bba8-b1229ca98c31",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e7dcbf63-907d-4545-8ff4-fba8c6c5c122"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0cdf6553-6c5c-4962-853d-246c3626538c",
      "position": 15,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to introduce the three data states — At Rest, In Transit, and In Use. Use the example of a message on your phone to show how encryption protects it during each stage: saving, sending, and using.\n- When it's saved on your device, symmetric encryption is used because it’s fast and efficient.\n- When it's sent across a network, asymmetric encryption is used to establish a secure connection — even over public internet. Then symmetric encryption protects the message itself.\n- When it's opened and being read or edited, it's typically decrypted so apps can access it. Then symmetric encryption protects the message itself.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If students struggle with the idea of data moving between states, draw a quick timeline on the board:\n* Saved → Sent → Opened, and label each with the encryption type used.\n\nThis can help visual learners see how one message moves through each protection step."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0cdf6553-6c5c-4962-853d-246c3626538c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e7dcbf63-907d-4545-8ff4-fba8c6c5c122"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4b174b5f-70b1-44b3-9a7c-e241bcdc12ef",
      "position": 16,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4b174b5f-70b1-44b3-9a7c-e241bcdc12ef",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e7dcbf63-907d-4545-8ff4-fba8c6c5c122"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a5160a5a-e8e8-4fcb-9775-214f6938d226",
      "position": 17,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 9, Level 1 in Code Studio to answer three reflection questions about the encryption method they created.",
        "progression_name": "My Encryption",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If time permits, consider displaying anonymous student responses and facilitating a brief class discussion:\n- \"Why did some people say their method was symmetric?\"\n- \"Did anyone change their mind about which data state theirs works best for?\"\n- \"What would make one type easier or harder to use in real life?\"\n\nThis reinforces key concepts and highlights diverse student thinking in a low-stakes way."
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "Student responses in Level 1 can be used as a formative assessment of the lesson's key objectives:\n- Describe how encryption helps protect data.\n- Differentiate between symmetric and asymmetric encryption.\n- Apply encryption concepts to different data states\n\nAs students submit their responses, circulate to spot-check for:\n- Clear descriptions of how the keys work (e.g., “same key” vs. “public/private pair”)\n- Correct identification of symmetric or asymmetric based on key structure\n- Reasoned justification for data at rest vs. in transit, using concepts like speed, usability, or connection setup\n\n If students are struggling, try the following:\n- Reteach key concepts using a quick visual recap: “If both people already have the same key = symmetric. If one person can send a locked message without knowing the recipient = asymmetric.”\n- Use a simple worked example on the board (e.g., shifting letters with one rule vs. needing two pieces of info to unlock)\n- Have students discuss their answers in pairs and revise for clarity\n- Revisit the data states table or the encryption diagram and ask: “Would your method work if the other person didn’t already know the key?” or  “Could this be used in real-time, like for a text message?”"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a5160a5a-e8e8-4fcb-9775-214f6938d226",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e7dcbf63-907d-4545-8ff4-fba8c6c5c122"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "70792c98-dc63-4594-a56c-cbb69fec74c4",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day. Direct students record their thoughts in their Unit Guide. Then, have students turn to a partner and share their answers.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If time permits, consider asking a few students to share with the whole class. You can record answers on the board or just spotlight key ideas aloud."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "70792c98-dc63-4594-a56c-cbb69fec74c4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "673e8be0-0ea4-40f9-a7a4-d8235a898768"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "46085c11-8240-4323-91e0-fa357ab5f365",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "46085c11-8240-4323-91e0-fa357ab5f365",
        "lesson_activity.key": "673e8be0-0ea4-40f9-a7a4-d8235a898768"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a4b76056-e525-44e1-b9cc-877590132ecd",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Key Vocabulary.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 9, Level 2 to complete the End of Lesson Survey.",
        "progression_name": "Student Survey"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a4b76056-e525-44e1-b9cc-877590132ecd",
        "lesson_activity.key": "673e8be0-0ea4-40f9-a7a4-d8235a898768"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c3d58d7b-d4da-44dc-946e-d7ff05215dea",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *You've just built a new encrypted messaging app, and you're confident the encryption is solid. But someone says, \"With AI, you might still be in trouble.\" How could AI help protect your app? How could AI find ways around  your encryption?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should highlight that AI can find weaknesses around an encrypted system, such as weak passwords or vulnerable settings. They should also begin to see that AI can help protect systems too — by generating strong passwords, detecting unusual activity, or blocking threats.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c3d58d7b-d4da-44dc-946e-d7ff05215dea",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f54d6955-bd0d-481f-a1fe-1aaf432e7f0f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "85e026ec-f081-4249-b258-066aa6b647f7",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullseye-arrow\"></i> **Goal of this activity:** Help students recognize how AI tools can both attack and defend password systems by identifying patterns. Students will begin to understand that AI spots and scales patterns. This sets up the tradeoff: AI can crack weak passwords, but it can also help make systems more secure.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the two AI roles. Ask students to turn to a neighbor and talk about:\n- *How is AI involved on both sides of this situation?*\n- *Can AI be both the problem and the solution? Why or why not?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should identify that AI can crack weak passwords using pattern recognition, while also help defenders block attacks and improve security systems. They should begin to wrestle with the idea that AI creates new vulnerabilities and new protections.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Put students into groups of two or three.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each group of students a copy of the AI in Encryption activity guide.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Password Pattern-Finding"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "85e026ec-f081-4249-b258-066aa6b647f7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c5cac6b8-0250-4966-8626-0f984f71d48a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d9c2ddd8-0bdf-48a0-b420-e75787c356a0",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "You'll be working together to think like an AI system – scanning a social media profile and past passwords to look for patterns. Your goal is to figure out how this person makes their passwords, and what they might choose next.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d9c2ddd8-0bdf-48a0-b420-e75787c356a0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c5cac6b8-0250-4966-8626-0f984f71d48a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7f9b06df-4425-4fa9-b344-2b9913ef4556",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to complete Part 1 of the activity guide. In their groups, students should analyze Maya's profile and past passwords to identify a pattern and predict two new passwords she might create.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain how AI can learn passwords by recognizing patterns and being trained on massive collections of leaked passwords and publicly available personal data.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students go to Lesson 10, Level 1. Use AI Chat to generate guesses for Maya's next password. Have groups discuss what they notice about the AI's guesses — what's similar, what's different, and what stands out.",
        "progression_name": "AI Generate Password Guesses"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7f9b06df-4425-4fa9-b344-2b9913ef4556",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c5cac6b8-0250-4966-8626-0f984f71d48a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e3377ae5-ac50-4b48-bfac-cefba0ec5c03",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Share one benefit and one harm of using AI in password pattern-finding.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should recognize that AI can spot patterns that make passwords easier to crack, which is a serious risk if attackers use it. But AI can also be used to protect users, like warning people about weak passwords or known password leaks.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "As students discuss the benefits and harms of AI in password cracking, encourage them to think beyond just what AI does and focus on who is using it and why. Prompt them with:\n- Who is using the AI? (Is it a hacker? A school IT team? A big tech company?)\n- How is it being used? (To guess passwords? To monitor security? To help users?)\n- What could go wrong? (Could it flag the wrong person? Be misused? Invade privacy?)"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e3377ae5-ac50-4b48-bfac-cefba0ec5c03",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c5cac6b8-0250-4966-8626-0f984f71d48a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7ca30363-ab70-4b03-99bc-f205aa9baac5",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7ca30363-ab70-4b03-99bc-f205aa9baac5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c5cac6b8-0250-4966-8626-0f984f71d48a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "42d8cdb3-b307-4fb2-a0ab-6ecf40b48555",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that when we use encrypted messaging apps, like Signal, WhatsApp, or even iMessage, the messages we send are protected. They're scrambled so no one, not even the app itself, can read them. But that protection usually only applies to the content of the message. Other information,  like who you messaged, when, how often, and for how long, can still be visible! That's called metadata. Metadata doesn't include what you said, but it still reveals patterns. And AI can analyze that data to make guesses about what kind of conversation you're having even without seeing the message itself."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "42d8cdb3-b307-4fb2-a0ab-6ecf40b48555",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c5cac6b8-0250-4966-8626-0f984f71d48a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9c9d2060-7be5-4d89-b697-81c20d44a9c9",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullseye-arrow\"></i> **Goal of this activity:** Help students recognize that AI tools can both protect and undermine encrypted messaging systems. Even when message content is private, AI can still find patterns in metadata and make powerful guesses. Students should begin to see how AI raises new questions about what \"secure\" really means.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to reveal both AI uses. Then ask students to turn to a partner and discuss:\n- *How is AI involved on both sides of this situation?*\n- *What’s surprising about AI's ability here?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should recognize that AI can help encrypt and protect messages, but it can also be used to infer patterns from metadata to help protect users from harmful behaviors. This introduces a key tradeoff: AI adds powerful tools for safety and moderation, but it also raises new risks for privacy and fairness, even when encryption is in place.",
        "duration": "20",
        "name": "Messaging Metadata Inference"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9c9d2060-7be5-4d89-b697-81c20d44a9c9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c5cac6b8-0250-4966-8626-0f984f71d48a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6cb9afab-307f-44bf-9706-cfc95c1243c3",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "You're going to look at metadata from different chat conversations. Metadata isn't the actual message content. It's just info about who messaged whom, when, how often, and how long the messages were. Your job is to think like an AI system: What might the AI assume is going on in the conversation? Then decide, based on the metadata, would the system think this looks risky and flag it? And do you, as a human, think it should be flagged?",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6cb9afab-307f-44bf-9706-cfc95c1243c3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c5cac6b8-0250-4966-8626-0f984f71d48a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "dfccc31a-e2df-4ba9-b7d3-fac2216bdf9c",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to complete Part 2 of the activity guide. In their groups, students will analyze chat metadata, make a guess about what kind of conversation it might represent, and decide whether AI would and should flag it for bullying, spam, or off-task behavior.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Some students may struggle with the idea that AI can make judgments without seeing message content. Remind them: AI is using only patterns in the metadata  not the words themselves. Encourage students to:\n- Think about how their own texting patterns might look from the outside.\n- Moderation systems that have flagged them in the past for spam or potential bot activity."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "dfccc31a-e2df-4ba9-b7d3-fac2216bdf9c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c5cac6b8-0250-4966-8626-0f984f71d48a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7d8f76dd-cf7c-4b3a-99ae-439dee3a8645",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7d8f76dd-cf7c-4b3a-99ae-439dee3a8645",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c5cac6b8-0250-4966-8626-0f984f71d48a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "85068184-1264-4574-a127-1d6fe45fc3fa",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Now that you've made your own guesses using metadata, let's see how an AI system compares. Like many real-world systems, it's trained on large datasets and can make fast predictions, but it doesn't always get it right. Your job is to look at what it came up with and decide: What might it get right? And what could it miss?",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "85068184-1264-4574-a127-1d6fe45fc3fa",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c5cac6b8-0250-4966-8626-0f984f71d48a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d56e1c7d-93ad-4583-b835-342a2eff573f",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students go to Lesson 10, Level 2. Use AI Chat to analyze metadata from one of the assigned chats. Once results are generated, students should discuss with a partner: What do you think it got right? What might it get wrong?",
        "progression_name": "AI Metadata Analysis"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d56e1c7d-93ad-4583-b835-342a2eff573f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c5cac6b8-0250-4966-8626-0f984f71d48a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e3c945a1-ad6a-49d0-a768-10129f74ac77",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "description": "You've seen how AI can be used to analyze passwords and metadata – sometimes to protect systems, and sometimes in ways that raise concerns. Now it's your turn to decide what you think a school should do. You'll choose a solution for how a school might use AI in its encrypted messaging system and then defend your choice using the benefits and trade offs we've discussed and from the provided table.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e3c945a1-ad6a-49d0-a768-10129f74ac77",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c5cac6b8-0250-4966-8626-0f984f71d48a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c7d2c2f7-c1ba-49a2-af11-854a9fb4947a",
      "position": 14,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students go to Lesson 10, Level 3. Ask them to choose a solution they think the school's encrypted messaging app should use, and write a short explanation of their choice, using at least one benefit and one tradeoff from the Solutions and Trade Offs table.",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding",
        "remarks": true,
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If time permits, use the View Student Responses to run a brief discussion asking students to compare the strategies they came up with on Level 3."
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The free response level in Lesson 10, Level 3 can be used as a formative assessment of the lesson objectives. If students are struggling:\n- Revisit AI Chat levels to review how AI to review how AI detects patterns and why that can both help and harm.\n- Consider pairing students or using sentence starters to support their responses.\n\nTeachers can also provide written feedback, prompting students to clarify:\n- Who benefits and who might be overlooked\n- How the solution balances competing values (safety, privacy, control)"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c7d2c2f7-c1ba-49a2-af11-854a9fb4947a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c5cac6b8-0250-4966-8626-0f984f71d48a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "09448d90-b912-4a64-8f9f-91ca929399c6",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students take out their AI Powered Threat and Defenses Unit Guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students respond to the Question of the Day in their Unit Guide. Then, direct students to pair up with their neighbor and share their answers. Have partners add one follow-up thought or reaction to their partner's response.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 10, Level 4 to complete the End of Lesson Survey."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "09448d90-b912-4a64-8f9f-91ca929399c6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1689e637-3081-48cd-86a8-b2f75408ce4f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1c992866-3066-4b85-9d91-b96ea1da879b",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Student Survey"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1c992866-3066-4b85-9d91-b96ea1da879b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7439fb75-2c6d-4c75-8f45-4047dca14070"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "051a85f1-cb73-4b65-a202-6d999b5d9c27",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullseye-arrow\"></i> **Goal of this activity:** Help students experience the challenge of overly complex security requirements and begin reflecting on the tradeoffs between strong security and user-friendly design.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a half sheet of blank paper. If using full sheets, have them tear or cut them in half.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If you'd rather do this warm up digitally, use the interactive version of the password game at https://neal.fun/password-game — but limit students to just 3–5 rules for timing.\n\nYou can also simplify the activity by running it as a whole-class game where everyone suggests passwords out loud and the class votes thumbs up/thumbs down."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "051a85f1-cb73-4b65-a202-6d999b5d9c27",
        "lesson_activity.key": "14e8da95-7bba-4c22-9032-a44257e7dd78"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "dd6323db-6252-4c69-83bf-7393675fb1b6",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "dd6323db-6252-4c69-83bf-7393675fb1b6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "14e8da95-7bba-4c22-9032-a44257e7dd78"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b41ecd57-4e2a-4e77-8c7c-21c709a4f39c",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain how to play the Password Game with their partner.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Some students may take the task too literally or try to create \"perfect\" passwords that pass every rule immediately. Let them know that struggling is expected—it's part of the experience and leads into today’s big idea."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b41ecd57-4e2a-4e77-8c7c-21c709a4f39c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "14e8da95-7bba-4c22-9032-a44257e7dd78"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "225bba72-e44e-46d6-ba2e-46d6b49147e1",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "225bba72-e44e-46d6-ba2e-46d6b49147e1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "14e8da95-7bba-4c22-9032-a44257e7dd78"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e76c52a5-d9c4-430f-a66f-e523715dcb9b",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Give students 30–60 seconds to write a password that meets this first rule. Let them know it doesn't have to be perfect — it just needs to be at least 8 characters long. Have them trade papers with their partner and give a thumbs up or down.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Some students may try to include extra rules right away (like special characters). Encourage them to keep it simple for now — they'll have time to build on it later."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e76c52a5-d9c4-430f-a66f-e523715dcb9b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "14e8da95-7bba-4c22-9032-a44257e7dd78"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e5e384e0-ea39-4b63-8ee9-f99d0b2ed310",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e5e384e0-ea39-4b63-8ee9-f99d0b2ed310",
        "lesson_activity.key": "14e8da95-7bba-4c22-9032-a44257e7dd78"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "78fcdf1a-9ea5-4ff6-99ce-0e9ac42809dd",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Give students 30–60 seconds to update their password to include at least one special character, while still keeping it at least 8 characters long. Remind them to trade papers with their partner and give a thumbs up or down.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Some students might try to start from scratch each round. Encourage them to build on their existing password — that's part of the challenge and the point of the activity."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "78fcdf1a-9ea5-4ff6-99ce-0e9ac42809dd",
        "lesson_activity.key": "14e8da95-7bba-4c22-9032-a44257e7dd78"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "45a8dd62-8f95-4eb4-8527-bd2feccca435",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "45a8dd62-8f95-4eb4-8527-bd2feccca435",
        "lesson_activity.key": "14e8da95-7bba-4c22-9032-a44257e7dd78"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7ebbb928-51f7-4038-a060-5f6c487b7fcb",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Give students 30–60 seconds to update their password to include the name of any month — while still keeping all previous rules. Then trade papers with their partner again for a new thumbs up/down check.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Some students may abbreviate (e.g., \"Jan\" instead of \"January\") or use part of a month name. Decide ahead of time whether to allow abbreviations, or let students decide together during peer review."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7ebbb928-51f7-4038-a060-5f6c487b7fcb",
        "lesson_activity.key": "14e8da95-7bba-4c22-9032-a44257e7dd78"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7e361727-dbb4-4c56-a7d6-486123edd30c",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7e361727-dbb4-4c56-a7d6-486123edd30c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "14e8da95-7bba-4c22-9032-a44257e7dd78"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4d17f5dd-4e35-4dc2-b187-f13d9348eb46",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Give students about 1 minute for this round — it may take longer to calculate or revise their password. Remind them to double-check that their digits add up to 25 and that they’re still following all the previous rules. Then trade and give thumbs up or down with their partner.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Give students 30–60 seconds to update their password. They must include a valid two-letter element symbol (e.g., Na, He) while still keeping all prior rules. Then trade with their partner and check for a thumbs up or down.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Some students may just pick any two capital letters — remind them it must be a real element symbol (like \"Fe\" for iron). Allow students to reference the periodic table if needed. You can also let them brainstorm a few common elements as a class (e.g., O, H, Fe, He, Na, Cl) before writing."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4d17f5dd-4e35-4dc2-b187-f13d9348eb46",
        "lesson_activity.key": "14e8da95-7bba-4c22-9032-a44257e7dd78"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "082d8271-aa3b-4b6c-a175-f09a7e7f5af9",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "082d8271-aa3b-4b6c-a175-f09a7e7f5af9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "14e8da95-7bba-4c22-9032-a44257e7dd78"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a3acfbf1-4cf3-4564-badd-994be59e6ffe",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click the animated slide to display the prompts.\n- *Which rules felt most frustrating?*\n- *At what point did security requirements get in the way of actually finishing the task?*\n- *Have you ever experienced this kind of tradeoff in real life?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should recognize that while strong passwords are important, security can sometimes feel excessive or unfair, especially when it blocks users from doing what they need to do. The goal here is to set up the idea that usable design matters just as much as protection, especially for people with different needs or situations."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a3acfbf1-4cf3-4564-badd-994be59e6ffe",
        "lesson_activity.key": "14e8da95-7bba-4c22-9032-a44257e7dd78"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "db77b309-cc10-43bb-b815-d9a00e58742b",
      "position": 14,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Your passwords became highly secure...but at what cost? You probably noticed that the more rules we added, the harder it became to actually finish the task. And that's the tricky part of designing for security: protecting people without making the system frustrating or impossible to use. Today, we're going to look at what happens when that balance is off — and what we might be able to do about it.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "db77b309-cc10-43bb-b815-d9a00e58742b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "14e8da95-7bba-4c22-9032-a44257e7dd78"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e14109b2-94d8-48cd-910e-d3fa2d690ee6",
      "position": 15,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e14109b2-94d8-48cd-910e-d3fa2d690ee6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "14e8da95-7bba-4c22-9032-a44257e7dd78"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5b198c96-063f-4aca-96db-cf0bf877c41b",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullseye-arrow\"></i> **Goal of this activity:** Recognize that well-meaning security measures can create barriers when they are not designed with diverse users in mind. This sets up the usability/security tradeoff and builds empathy.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Display the real-world scenarios on the next slides one at a time. Pause after each to ask the discussion questions.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-video-camera\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Video:** Show the  \"____________\" video.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Before playing the clip, remind students to think about the questions as they watch:\n- What problem is the security feature is trying to solve?\n- What went wrong for the user?\n- What was the intended benefit and unintended consequences\n\nAfter reading the cartoon, ask for a few quick responses before moving to the next scenario.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should understand that while auto-logout features are designed to protect sensitive information, they can create major usability issues—especially for users who work slowly, need extra time, or pause to think. This case highlights how strict time-based security can unintentionally exclude users with legitimate needs and disrupt tasks in high-pressure situations like testing.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Case Study",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If students say the design is \"dumb,\" prompt them to consider why it might have seemed like a good idea at the time. Use this moment to build empathy for designers who must balance competing priorities. Ask: \"Why might this have made sense to the designer?\" or \"What's a user situation they might not have anticipated?\""
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5b198c96-063f-4aca-96db-cf0bf877c41b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3de69b07-a920-4dfe-af4a-0b3295887ec2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "fdfbb30c-bfa8-4c0b-a8c1-0b3ec1bd914a",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "fdfbb30c-bfa8-4c0b-a8c1-0b3ec1bd914a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3de69b07-a920-4dfe-af4a-0b3295887ec2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "62f57fe3-ded7-4a72-a77d-2de411922181",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-video-camera\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Video:** Show the  \"____________\" video.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Before playing the clip, remind students to think about the questions as they watch:\n- What problem is the security feature is trying to solve?\n- What went wrong for the user?\n- What was the intended benefit and unintended consequences\n\nAfter reading the cartoon, ask for a few quick responses before moving to the next scenario.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should understand that while account lockout policies are meant to protect against hacking or repeated guessing, they can unfairly block legitimate users — especially those dealing with hardware issues, accessibility needs, or moments of stress. This case helps students see how rigid security rules can cause harm when they don't account for real-world conditions."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "62f57fe3-ded7-4a72-a77d-2de411922181",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3de69b07-a920-4dfe-af4a-0b3295887ec2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ff382023-c56f-4f76-a557-57e2aef92e8f",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullseye-arrow\"></i> **Goal of this activity:** Apply empathy and reasoning to redesign one flawed security feature for a user with accessibility needs, balancing both usability and security.",
        "duration": "20",
        "name": "Redesign Challenge"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ff382023-c56f-4f76-a557-57e2aef92e8f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3de69b07-a920-4dfe-af4a-0b3295887ec2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1a3d0d30-0601-408c-b939-2196cb03541f",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Now you're the secure system designer. Your job is to keep users safe, but also make sure the system actually works for them.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1a3d0d30-0601-408c-b939-2196cb03541f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3de69b07-a920-4dfe-af4a-0b3295887ec2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f592ca2d-ef26-467b-b762-ba3011a8e126",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Place students into groups of two.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each pair of students a copy of the Security vs Usability activity guide and Security vs Usability Matrix handout.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain to students that for Part 1, students pick a user and follow their interactions with 3 security features. For each, they'll decide how well it worked and place it on the Security vs. Usability Matrix. In Part 2, they'll pick one feature to revise or improve to better support the user.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Before students begin, emphasize that their goal isn't to \"get through it\" but to think carefully about how each security feature affects their user. This activity is about perspective-taking and tradeoffs — not speed."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f592ca2d-ef26-467b-b762-ba3011a8e126",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3de69b07-a920-4dfe-af4a-0b3295887ec2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "55e81b08-7447-4d22-9208-d9991842f65b",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "55e81b08-7447-4d22-9208-d9991842f65b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3de69b07-a920-4dfe-af4a-0b3295887ec2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d58ce13d-4e2a-4fc2-8efc-b24b79f85e5b",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 11, Level 1 to choose a persona and begin analyzing how their user interacts with different security features.",
        "progression_name": "Analyze the Experience"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d58ce13d-4e2a-4fc2-8efc-b24b79f85e5b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3de69b07-a920-4dfe-af4a-0b3295887ec2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3702ab94-e184-4824-8087-355a90ff7941",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Check that students are using the matrix meaningfully. Ask: \"Why do you think this feature was hard for your user?\" \"What makes this a high or low security choice?\" Ensure students are not focusing only on surface-level changes, prompt empathy and tradeoff analysis.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If students are unsure where to place a feature on the matrix, remind them that it's okay to make a best guess as long as they can explain their reasoning. There's often more than one valid answer — the goal is thoughtful justification, not perfect placement."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3702ab94-e184-4824-8087-355a90ff7941",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3de69b07-a920-4dfe-af4a-0b3295887ec2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "fa4f5c2b-c052-4d91-b11f-3f70825d3da5",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "fa4f5c2b-c052-4d91-b11f-3f70825d3da5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3de69b07-a920-4dfe-af4a-0b3295887ec2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1d6b3ecf-3ffa-4109-9814-27495d071429",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** When students are done with Part 1 of their activity guide (mapping security features for their chosen user), instruct them to move on to Part 2. They'll choose at least one security feature that landed in the low/low quadrant and revise it for better usability and/or security.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Ensure students are using the scaffolded sentence starters and fix ideas. Look for groups getting stuck and redirect them toward empathy-based reasoning instead.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage creativity and student voice. There's no perfect fix, what matters is thoughtfulness. Let students know that user-centered design involves revision and compromise."
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "You may choose to collect students’ completed activity guides and use them as a formative assessment for both lesson objectives:\n- Describe how a security feature might unintentionally create a barrier for users\n- Redesign a security feature to better balance security and usability\n\nUse the matrix placements and redesign write-ups to check whether students:\n- Identified realistic usability/security barriers from their persona’s perspective\n- Proposed thoughtful changes that improve one or both dimensions\n\nIf students struggle to explain the usability problem or only address one side of the tradeoff, consider reviewing common security tools in the next class and modeling how human-centered redesign can still protect users."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1d6b3ecf-3ffa-4109-9814-27495d071429",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3de69b07-a920-4dfe-af4a-0b3295887ec2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "48ca85e2-4147-4500-b9a1-33e60bd1075e",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "48ca85e2-4147-4500-b9a1-33e60bd1075e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3de69b07-a920-4dfe-af4a-0b3295887ec2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "92bf5974-fa17-4075-9129-e7eb2bef0cc8",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click the animated slide to display the prompts.\n- *What does it mean to design for both safety and usability?*\n- *How can thinking about real users lead to better security?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should understand that effective cybersecurity design requires balancing protection with usability — a system isn't truly secure if people can't use it. They should also recognize that thinking about real users' needs and barriers leads to more thoughtful, inclusive, and ultimately stronger security solutions.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If time allows, extend this into a creative reflection:\n- Have groups sketch a mini scene showing how the redesign works better\n- Or write a short dialogue between the user and the system\n- Display final matrix + redesign on the wall as a gallery walk"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "92bf5974-fa17-4075-9129-e7eb2bef0cc8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3de69b07-a920-4dfe-af4a-0b3295887ec2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3e16658d-3848-4842-ad40-63c828bce2b9",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students take out their AI Powered Threat and Defenses Unit Guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day. Invite students to briefly reflect on how today’s activity helped them answer this. What examples or tradeoffs stood out?\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students complete a quick sketch in their unit guide using the provided stick figure template. If they would like, they can add in rough sketches of items such as a phone or a desk with a laptop. In the speech bubble, they should write something the character might say that reflects a frustration, tradeoff, or design improvement idea related to security and usability. For example: \"Ugh, I can’t remember another 12-character password!\" or \"Why can't this app just let me log in with Face ID?\"",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If time allows, let students do a quick small-group share or walk around to see 2–3 classmates' sketches. Prompt them to notice any patterns in what people found frustrating or surprising about the tradeoffs."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3e16658d-3848-4842-ad40-63c828bce2b9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "dc2f25bd-78d0-407e-bda0-88e235e547d4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "55b537a3-81cb-4989-b6e3-31e55838cee3",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "55b537a3-81cb-4989-b6e3-31e55838cee3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "dc2f25bd-78d0-407e-bda0-88e235e547d4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0fb89567-fa9b-44c0-84a0-37f61c1ed424",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 11, Level 2 to complete the End of Lesson Survey."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0fb89567-fa9b-44c0-84a0-37f61c1ed424",
        "lesson_activity.key": "dc2f25bd-78d0-407e-bda0-88e235e547d4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f5dc8f94-2929-4ec9-b035-99586e1b2490",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Student Survey"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f5dc8f94-2929-4ec9-b035-99586e1b2490",
        "lesson_activity.key": "cbf935e0-cf42-47fa-8498-c9fb94f5d46c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "40c33b0b-a5d0-4cc1-8a99-91feb0f66066",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullseye-arrow\"></i> **Goal of this activity:** Have students surface everyday security layers they already use.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students write down as many security features they can in the given time. Provide an example or two if needed: FaceID (digital); key to unlock door (analog device). When time elapses, have students count how many security features or devices they were able to come up with. Then have a few volunteers share out some of their responses.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Why are there so many security steps? Could one tool have protected everything?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should be able to explain that there need to exist a variety of different types of security. This could be an opportunity to point out that there are preventative, detective, and corrective security measures. You might also have students reflect on redundancies in security systems, i.e. the misconception that more security measures = better security.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "40c33b0b-a5d0-4cc1-8a99-91feb0f66066",
        "lesson_activity.key": "0cf53532-6b11-4177-9c07-0902f7d2da9d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e8139f49-d4fe-406c-bffc-6e879b7ee512",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullseye-arrow\"></i> **Goal of this activity:** Students identify key system events in a chosen app. They analyze vulnerabilities and tag affected CIA/AAA pillars.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students take out their AI Powered Threat and Defenses Unit Guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *layered defenses*.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Explore Systems and Vulnerabilities"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e8139f49-d4fe-406c-bffc-6e879b7ee512",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1dbe7a64-f2e0-4e59-8a0c-a99a4c9cffde"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5b211ab3-91ae-44fc-a24b-f416bfa103c1",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Now that we've talked about how different security features, let's explore different systems that would benefit from layering different defenses.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5b211ab3-91ae-44fc-a24b-f416bfa103c1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1dbe7a64-f2e0-4e59-8a0c-a99a4c9cffde"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b125ce94-0476-4d75-ba7b-7a38ffe7fb51",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Put students into groups of two.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each pair of students a copy of the Layered Defenses Digital Activity Guide."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b125ce94-0476-4d75-ba7b-7a38ffe7fb51",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1dbe7a64-f2e0-4e59-8a0c-a99a4c9cffde"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5e841f86-5faa-4779-b6e7-c777ccf670f1",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 12, Level 1 to select one of the apps from the four choices. Direct students to explore the app by clicking through the different screens.",
        "progression_name": "Exploring Apps"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5e841f86-5faa-4779-b6e7-c777ccf670f1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1dbe7a64-f2e0-4e59-8a0c-a99a4c9cffde"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "11e45ade-f532-4e6f-a083-c6ff287f89db",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** As students explore the app they selected, have them complete the corresponding diagram in their Layered Defenses activity guide. They should use colored pencils shade in green, blue, and yellow on the app screen to represent the following:\n- Green: Where the user enters information (e.g., login, form)\n- Blue: Where the app saves and/or shows user information (e.g., dashboard, output)\n- Yellow: Where the app sends data out (e.g., cloud sync, email)\n\nFor each of the three app screens, have students identify:\n- At least one potential vulnerability\n- Tag the affected CIA pillar (Confidentiality, Integrity, Availability) or relevant AAA framework (Authentication, Authorization, and Auditing)\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Help support students who might be stuck by asking probing question like, \"What could go wrong here if someone wanted to attack this point? Which CIA pillar is impacted?\"",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Let students know that they don’t need to identify every single system event. As long as they identify one of each type (user input, data storage, data transit), they will be able to complete the activity guide. Use the Teacher Key as a model for what annotation and comments should look like. There is also an exemplar table for layered defenses and a vulnerability cheat sheet for all four apps."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "11e45ade-f532-4e6f-a083-c6ff287f89db",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1dbe7a64-f2e0-4e59-8a0c-a99a4c9cffde"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ac967965-1ed8-4eb8-92b1-bba7e86e1950",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ac967965-1ed8-4eb8-92b1-bba7e86e1950",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1dbe7a64-f2e0-4e59-8a0c-a99a4c9cffde"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6e191edf-fb1f-4afe-8f0c-bc35702a4ad4",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullseye-arrow\"></i> **Goal of this activity:** Students apply the idea of defense-in-depth by choosing appropriate defenses for each vulnerability—without exceeding budget limits.",
        "duration": "20",
        "name": "Choose Layered Defenses Within a Budget"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6e191edf-fb1f-4afe-8f0c-bc35702a4ad4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1dbe7a64-f2e0-4e59-8a0c-a99a4c9cffde"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ff43df0e-b94b-49a9-9cb8-5d6a3358ed8b",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Now that you've spotted the vulnerabilities, you’re the defender. Your job is to layer in security protections — but stay within your limits.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ff43df0e-b94b-49a9-9cb8-5d6a3358ed8b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1dbe7a64-f2e0-4e59-8a0c-a99a4c9cffde"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "877230c2-64b3-45e3-a4df-ad662a7e0d4f",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Distribute one Defense Menu handout per student. Remind students to save their copy for when they begin working on the final project. Have students go to the Layered Defense Table in their Slide Deck (last slide).  Explain the challenge:\n- Each student pair gets 5 Cost Points and 5 Friction Points\n- They must choose 2-3 defenses total to apply to their identified vulnerabilities.\n- Have students complete the table by filling out each column. Note: Students might not need every row in the table, depending on how many defenses they choose.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Ask, \"Which vulnerability is this helping with? Why this defense over another? Are you staying under budget?\"",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage students to think like designers balancing real-world constraints.\n\nOptional extension: Ask them which defense is the weakest link—and what backup layer might cover its failure."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "877230c2-64b3-45e3-a4df-ad662a7e0d4f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1dbe7a64-f2e0-4e59-8a0c-a99a4c9cffde"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "41a8b8ec-7e04-44d5-b153-e087e324370b",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "41a8b8ec-7e04-44d5-b153-e087e324370b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1dbe7a64-f2e0-4e59-8a0c-a99a4c9cffde"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "31a4292f-62cb-4ab8-afa6-0a7453e6e3be",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Show an example of how the Defense Menu works (e.g., CAPTCHA at login = cost 1, friction 1; email alerts = cost 2, friction 1). Remind students that they have up to 5 cost and 5 friction points to use, and can always use less.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n- *What would have happened if you used only one defense?*\n- *Which defense did your group choose because it balanced protection and ease of use?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should recognize that layered defenses offer stronger protection than using just one, and that effective cybersecurity involves balancing security with ease of use. Listen for reasoning about tradeoffs and which defenses felt \"worth it\" within their budget.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Consider doing a live \"budget check\" with one group’s solution on the board to model how tradeoffs were made."
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "Use student responses in the discussion to check conceptual understanding of defense layering and tradeoffs.\n\nIf students show strong understanding:\n- Move forward to the next lesson or warm-up with confidence. Invite 1–2 students to summarize what “layered defense” means in their own words.\n\nIf students show partial or shallow understanding:\n- Revisit one group’s app map as a class and unpack how their defenses work together.\n\nAsk:\n- What if this layer failed—what would still protect the system?\n- Would this combo work for every user?\n\nIf students are off track or disengaged:\n- Do a quick reteach using a different app screen as a worked example. Let students re-map one vulnerability and defense combo before finishing the lesson."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "31a4292f-62cb-4ab8-afa6-0a7453e6e3be",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1dbe7a64-f2e0-4e59-8a0c-a99a4c9cffde"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f16e0336-1595-43cd-a33e-8c0a81e13b55",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Unit Guide can be collected as an assessment of the objectives in this lesson."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f16e0336-1595-43cd-a33e-8c0a81e13b55",
        "lesson_activity.key": "dbb0f240-3861-4e74-a188-977846cf5c8f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "98a2c7b2-f5cf-41e3-88ee-ea13ddf57af0",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "98a2c7b2-f5cf-41e3-88ee-ea13ddf57af0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "dbb0f240-3861-4e74-a188-977846cf5c8f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3f49a9f8-7ac0-4269-8cb3-c928a7672ecd",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Key Vocabulary.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 12, Level 2 to complete the End of Lesson Survey."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3f49a9f8-7ac0-4269-8cb3-c928a7672ecd",
        "lesson_activity.key": "dbb0f240-3861-4e74-a188-977846cf5c8f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b94a6d94-4ce5-4382-84e7-524a4172d033",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Student Survey"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b94a6d94-4ce5-4382-84e7-524a4172d033",
        "lesson_activity.key": "78ed615e-f8ad-49f8-bb47-c51af0bbf808"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "71f7d22f-636c-4dfc-8acc-4dd788b34a1a",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How might different people (like a student and a principal) use or experience the same app or platform in different ways?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should start to think about how different users might need the same system or application customized to fit their unique needs. For example, different users might need different types of log-in systems, different access to information stored on the platform, and different controls. If students answer too generally (e.g., “they use it differently”), consider following up with: \"What might be different about what they need from the system? Or what they’re allowed to do or see?\" This will nudge students to start thinking in terms of user needs, access, control, and even risk, which directly supports Day 1’s system issue identification.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Warm Up"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "71f7d22f-636c-4dfc-8acc-4dd788b34a1a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "774a9238-9c46-4594-b1b4-89d1a8847e1e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9ad41493-a682-4281-8387-4242096e5c32",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullseye-arrow\"></i> **Goal of this activity:** Introduce students to the Designing Secure Systems project, its goals, and expected deliverables.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Place students into pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each pair a copy of the Designing Secure Systems Project Planning Guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Welcome students to the Designing Secure Systems project. Let them know they’ll be using their Project Planning Guide to work through a series of steps across the next few lessons.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Instruct students to review the assessment criteria rubric and final deliverables on the last page of the Project Planning Guide. Encourage students to notice what strong work looks like in each area and think about what \"extensive evidence\" might look like in their own project.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n- *What do you notice about the project rubric?*\n- *What does success look like for this project?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students share what they notice about the project requirements and rubric and identify the tasks they will need to complete for this project.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Project Overview",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Consider charting student responses about what success looks like so they can refer back to it as a checklist or anchor throughout the project."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9ad41493-a682-4281-8387-4242096e5c32",
        "lesson_activity.key": "774a9238-9c46-4594-b1b4-89d1a8847e1e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "00a8c89a-f1f6-4c8a-bba2-036bc9c28df1",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "00a8c89a-f1f6-4c8a-bba2-036bc9c28df1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "774a9238-9c46-4594-b1b4-89d1a8847e1e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "13c5d2a2-ad8b-421c-b2fd-cc5ac0d98bf8",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What barriers do you anticipate to achieving success on this project?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students identify barriers they anticipate and share any questions they have about the project.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If you hear the same barrier come up more than once, jot it on the board and offer a strategy or remind them of support tools like the AI Chatbot levels."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "13c5d2a2-ad8b-421c-b2fd-cc5ac0d98bf8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "774a9238-9c46-4594-b1b4-89d1a8847e1e"
      }
    },
